1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 ( 2. f4 { We start off with the infamous King's Gambit! It may often just be a meme opening for online rapid and blitz but it has a rich history and cannot be underestimated. It was played right from Morphy times and still occasionally features at GM level. Our priority against such openings is to prepare something which is easy to learn and that we can remember for a long time. } ) ( 2. Nc3 { This is called the Vienna game. White usually wants to go for a delayed King's Gambit with the move f4 next or he can play more slowly with g3. We see this in the 2nd chapter. } 2... Nc6 { I came across this move only when preparing my files for this course. It cuts down on a lot of lines for us. Earlier, I automatically prepared the move Nf6. I have never faced this variation as Black in an OTB game though as it is completely out of practice. } ) ( 2. d4 { We will continue looking at some early dubious lines, often involving gambits in the 3rd chapter. It does break the general principles since White is not supposed to get his queen out so early. } ) ( 2. Bc4 { The Bishop's opening is more common than the lines we have seen so far. It is often also a weapon against Petroff players. Seeing that we are not going for the Petroff I don't mind allowing White to transpose back to an Italian. } 2... Nf6 3. d3 Nc6 4. Nc3 Bc5 { This is a simple move which keeps our play consistent with the Italian lines. We are also preparing a devious surprise for our opponent on the next move. } ) 2... Nc6 3. Nc3 ( 3. d4 { In modern times, the Scotch is getting more popular due to the huge amount of theory in the Ruy Lopez and now also in the Italian. It has been championed by players like Kasparov in the past. } 3... exd4 4. Nxd4 ( 4. Bc4 { This is an interesting system where White gives up the pawn on d4 to speed up his development. This is the only move order to get this position by force. We do not allow this via the Italian move order. However, both Nf6 and Bc5 here give White options to transpose back to the Italian. I will recommend an independent option. } 4... Bb4+ { This is a very provocative move as we end up opening the center for White's pieces. } ) 4... Nf6 5. Nxc6 bxc6 { We will take a look at a few sidelines on move 6 in the 6th chapter. } 6. e5 ( 6. Nd2 { This was introduced back to top-level chess by Vidit when he beat Tari with excellent prep back in 2022. } ) ( 6. Bd3 { This is the second most played move here. White wants to castle as soon as he can but allows us to get control over the center. } ) ( 6. Qe2 { This is usually played after the inclusion of the moves e5 and Qe7. Here, White goes Qe2 first and will meet Qe7 with Nc3. It has been played by Erigaisi in classical chess. } ) 6... Qe7 7. Qe2 Nd5 8. c4 { This is the main line in the Scotch variation trying to kick the knight to a more passive square. It does weaken the queenside as we will try to go after it with Ba6 soon. } ( 8. h4 { This has been the new trend in the Scotch for the last 5-8 years. Inspired by Alpha Zero, White advances his 'h' pawn. It can be useful in multiple ways- to gain space with h5, to go Bg5 or to get Rh3. This has been covered in the 7th chapter. } ) 8... Ba6 { There is no need to move the knight from d5. The usual plan here is to go g6 and Bg7 next. We have some other interesting plans though in the main lines. We take a deep look at this in the 8th chapter. } ) ( 3. c3 { This is called the Ponziani variation and is one of the oldest chess openings having been advocated by Howard Staunton back in the 19th century. White is preparing to go d4 next. We see this also in the 5th chapter. } ) 3... Nf6 { The Four Knights variation is very popular among club players and it is often the first opening they play. It follows the general rule to develop the knights before the bishops. There are a few players who play this ambitiously with White but also a bunch of players who want to be very solid. We will try to find the balance between playing "correct chess" and trying to get a fighting game. In the 9th chapter, we will see a bunch of random moves here. We will usually go d5 if given the chance. } 4. Bb5 { I call this the Four Knights Spanish due to the bishop on b5. We have two major options- to copy White with Bg4 or to go Nd4. } ( 4. d4 { I call this the Four Knight Scotch and it is a pretty annoying line as White is very solid. He can also do this via the Scotch move order but it gives us more options. } 4... exd4 5. Nxd4 { Here I was trying to choose between two options- the big main line with Bb4 or to go for the Nxe4 line which is more likely to surprise our opponent. But the drawback there was that White has a few options to force a draw and some which are pretty critical. I did not see its benefit and I want something which we can play for a long time. } ) 4... Nd4 { Whenever I was not well prepared I used to go Bb4 as those lines are easier to play without preparation. But they lead to slightly unpleasant positions. Nd4 equalises almost by force and will be my recommendation here. } *[Event "?"]
