1. e4 e5 2. f4 { The infamous King's Gambit! It may often just be a meme opening for online rapid and blitz but it has a rich history and cannot be underestimated. It was played right from Morphy times and still occasionally features at GM level. Our priority against such openings is to prepare something which is easy to learn and that we can remember for a long time. } 2... exf4 { Of course, we take the pawn. The major advantage is that it weakens White's kingside. } 3. Nf3 { This is the more natural move stopping Qh4 and bringing the knight in contact with the center. We have a few different ways of playing here. } ( 3. Bc4 { This is a provocative move inviting the check on h4. } 3... Nc6 { We bring our knight into the game keeping an eye on the d4 pawn. Now, Qh4 and Bc5 is a big threat. } 4. d4 ( 4. Nf3 { Typically, the move Nf3 is an indication for us to go for the move } 4... g5 5. d4 Bg7 6. h4 { White has to try something quick to justify his pawn sacrifice. } 6... h6 7. Nc3 d6 $15 ) 4... Nf6 { We want to meet the move e5 with d5 getting control over the center. Otherwise, it is not easy to defend the pawn on e4. } 5. e5 ( 5. Nc3 Bb4 6. Ne2 ( 6. Qd3 d5 $17 ) 6... f3 $1 { We weaken the kingside giving back our extra pawn. } 7. gxf3 d5 8. exd5 Nxd5 9. O-O Nxc3 10. bxc3 Bd6 $15 { We have a much safer king and a better pawn structure. } ) 5... d5 6. Be2 Ne4 7. Bxf4 f6 { We want to force White to take on e5 with the 'd' pawn and go Bc5. } 8. Nf3 fxe5 9. Nxe5 Nxe5 10. Bxe5 Bb4+ $1 { We want to castle first and keep the White king on e1. } 11. c3 O-O $1 12. Bf3 Qh4+ 13. g3 Qh3 $36 { [%cal Gc8g4] } ) 3... Nf6 { I feel that this is the easiest line to play and remember. I played this once in 2018 and have never faced the King's Gambit again. We can get our knight to h5 to defend the pawn on f4. } 4. e5 { This is the most logical move forcing our knight to h5. This is an exception to the rule that knights on the rim are dim. It keeps an eye on the kingside defending the pawn on f4. Moves like g3 also get harder to achieve. } ( 4. Nc3 { White wants to go e5 followed by Bc4 next taking control over the center. } 4... d5 $1 { We are happy to open the center and trade some pieces. } 5. exd5 ( 5. e5 $6 { Is a much worse version with the knight on c3 which is useless here. } 5... Nh5 6. d4 Nc6 7. g3 g5 $17 { We will meet gxf4 with g4 and get our queen to h4. } ) 5... Nxd5 6. Nxd5 { helps us get our queen out. } ( 6. Bc4 { allows us to trade the queens after } 6... Qe7+ 7. Qe2 Nxc3 8. dxc3 Qxe2+ 9. Bxe2 Bd6 $15 { We reach a comfortable endgame and White has to work hard to win the pawn back. } ) ( 6. Bb5+ { White wants to get Qe2 next and eventually bring the bishop to b3. } 6... c6 7. Qe2+ Be6 8. Nxd5 Qxd5 9. Ba4 Nd7 10. Bb3 Qb5 $1 { We force the trade of queens getting a comfortable endgame. } 11. Qxb5 cxb5 $15 12. d4 Bd6 $15 { [%cal Gd7f6] } ) 6... Qxd5 7. d4 Be7 8. Bd3 ( 8. c4 { does not help White at all. } 8... Qd6 $17 ) 8... g5 { We can preserve our pawn on f4 here and it is not easy for White to create anything on the kingside. } 9. O-O ( 9. Qe2 Bf5 $1 10. Bc4 Qe4 $15 { We have a comfortable endgame up a pawn. } ) 9... Bg4 10. h3 Bh5 11. Qe1 Bxf3 12. Rxf3 Nc6 13. c3 O-O-O $15 { Our king is safe on the queenside here while we can go f5 and start playing on the kingside. } ) 4... Nh5 5. d4 { White creates a threat of going g4 next. He has good control over the center. } ( 5. Bc4 { runs straight into } 5... d5 6. exd6 Bxd6 $17 ) ( 5. Qe2 { This was even played by Magnus and the point is that White wants to get his king to the queenside soon. It is objectively quite a bit better for Black though. } 5... Be7 6. d4 O-O 7. Nc3 d6 8. Bd2 Bg4 9. O-O-O Nd7 { All of this happened in the aforementioned game. It was definitely a huge bluff and Black has played perfect chess so far and is much better. Black did make some inaccuracies next but he went on to win the game. } 10. Qe1 Re8 { We are preparing to go for the move c5 next. } ( 10... c6 11. Be2 Re8 12. g3 $13 { 0-1 (23) Carlsen,M (2863) -Ding,L (2791) chess24.com INT 2020 } ) 11. Be2 c5 $17 ) ( 5. Be2 { This is pretty slow and can be met with } 5... g5 $1 6. O-O h6 { Our kingside structure is secure now. We will go d6 next and open the center. } 7. d4 d6 { [%cal Gh5g7,Gf8e7, Ge8g8] } 8. Re1 Be7 $17 ) 5... g6 $5 { This is a pretty rare move. We keep an eye on the knight on h5 and create a square on g7 for it. } ( 5... g5 6. Nfd2 $16 { [%cal Gd2e4] } ) 6. Nc3 { The aggresive approach planning to castle queenside. } ( 6. Bc4 { always runs into } 6... d5 7. Be2 g5 $17 ) ( 6. Qe2 Be7 7. Bd2 O-O 8. Nc3 d6 9. O-O-O Bg4 { transposes. } ) ( 6. Be2 { This is the tamer approach but White should win back the pawn on f4 eventually. The drawback is that our play is very easy and White is the one suffering to equalise- clearly not the plan when going for an aggressive opening. } 6... d6 7. O-O Nc6 8. Nc3 Bg7 9. exd6 cxd6 10. Kh1 Bg4 11. Nd5 O-O 12. Nxf4 { White finally wins back the pawn but his king is still an issue and we have better development. } 12... Nf6 $11 ) 6... d6 7. Qe2 Be7 8. Bd2 O-O 9. O-O-O { This is similar to the Magnus game we saw earlier but we have played the move g6 which is not useful here. } 9... Bg4 10. Qf2 ( 10. Qe4 { is met with } 10... c6 $1 11. g3 f5 12. exf6 Bxf6 $17 ) ( 10. g3 { White wants to open files to attack on the kingside. } 10... fxg3 11. Qg2 c5 $1 { We counter attack in the center. We want to win the pawn on e5. } 12. Be2 Nc6 13. dxc5 dxe5 $15 ) 10... dxe5 11. Be2 e4 $1 { We give the pawn back but keep the 'd' file closed. We are still up a pawn. } 12. Nxe4 Nd7 13. Rhe1 a5 $15 { We can continue with Ndf6 or play on the queenside. Our king is very safe on g8 here. } *[Event "?"]
