1. e4 e5 2. Nc3 { This is called the Vienna game. White usually wants to go for a delayed King's Gambit with the move f4 next or he can play more slowly with g3. } 2... Nc6 { I came across this move only when preparing my files for this course. It cuts down on a lot of lines for us. Earlier, I automatically prepared the move Nf6. I have never faced this variation as Black in an OTB game though as it is completely out of practice. } ( 2... Nf6 { This is the usual response to the Vienna but I think there is no need to allow the lines with } 3. f4 $5 ) 3. f4 { With the knight on c6 keeping an eye on d4 this is not an improvement over the traditional King's Gambit. } ( 3. g3 { This is the other independent option here. The fact that we have not played Nf6 is in our favour since we can get our knight to e7. } 3... a5 $5 { This may look very strange but we just want to go Bc5 next and the pawn on a5 stops Na4 ideas. It is also useful to gain space on the queenside. You would be very familiar with this if you checked out my database on the Italian. } ( 3... Bc5 4. Bg2 ( 4. Na4 $5 ) 4... d6 5. Na4 { This can often be an issue in these lines. } ) 4. Bg2 Bc5 5. Nge2 { We have the option of going either Nf6 or Nge7. } 5... Nf6 { I like this more here as we are not looking to go f5 anytime. We want to play in the center. } 6. O-O O-O 7. d3 ( 7. h3 Re8 8. Kh2 Nd4 { We play the same as in the main line. } 9. f4 d5 $1 { We do not need to prepare it. } 10. exd5 $2 Ra6 $19 { Our rook joins in the attack with Ng4 coming next. } ) 7... Re8 8. h3 Nd4 { I like this trade as we can now go for the move c6. } 9. Nxd4 ( 9. Kh2 c6 10. f4 d5 $11 ) 9... Bxd4 10. Kh2 c6 { We are going to go h6 followed by d5 next. } 11. f4 d5 $1 12. exd5 ( 12. Ne2 Ba7 $11 ) 12... cxd5 13. Nb5 Bb6 14. fxe5 Rxe5 { Our pawn on d5 may be a weakness in the endgame but our active pieces easily compensate for it in the middlegame. } 15. d4 { This happened in the game 0-1 (40) Korobov,A (2658) -Dardha,D (2610) Vrnjacka Banja 2023. I like the move } 15... Rf5 16. a4 ( 16. Bf4 Rh5 $15 { [%cal Gc8h3] } ) 16... Bd7 17. Rxf5 Bxf5 $11 ) 3... exf4 { Of course, we take the pawn. We are ready to go Qh4 next. } 4. Nf3 { Usually the drawback of Nf3 is that we are able to go } ( 4. d4 $5 { White allows the check as his king will be pretty decent on e2. } 4... Qh4+ 5. Ke2 b6 $1 { The bishop is heading to a6 or even b7 and we can follow it up with 0-0-0. } 6. Qd2 ( 6. Nb5 Qe7 $14 { We bring the queen back to target e4. If we crush the center it will be hard to survive for White. } 7. Nxc7+ Kd8 8. Nxa8 Qxe4+ 9. Kf2 Nxd4 $15 { We can always win the knight on a8. Bc5 is coming up soon. } ) 6... g5 { We first defend the pawn on f4 and also get the g7 square for the bishop. } 7. Kd1 Bb7 8. g3 Qh5+ 9. Be2 g4 10. Qxf4 ( 10. gxf4 f5 $19 { White has big issues with his development. } ) 10... Nxd4 11. Qxc7 Bc6 12. Qf4 Qc5 $15 { We have a ton of ideas here like h5, f5 or Bh6. White is in trouble. } ) 4... g5 $1 { We create the threat of going g4 next. } 5. g3 $1 { This is the best move trying to break our kingside. } ( 5. Bc4 $2 g4 6. O-O { This was tried by MVL twice but is just a complete bluff. } 6... gxf3 7. Qxf3 ( 7. Bxf7+ $2 Kxf7 8. Qxf3 { In the game 0-1 (30) Vachier Lagrave,M (2784) -Nakamura,H (2736) Chess.com INT 2020, Black should have just gone } 8... d6 9. Qxf4+ Nf6 $19 ) 7... Qh4 8. d4 Nxd4 9. Qd3 Ne6 $17 ) ( 5. d4 $2 { runs into } 5... g4 6. Ne5 Nxe5 7. dxe5 Qh4+ 8. g3 fxg3 9. Bg2 gxh2+ 10. Kf1 Bc5 $19 { 0-1 (31) Jobava,B (2603) -Karthikeyan,M (2606) Chess.com INT 2020 } ) ( 5. h4 $6 g4 6. Ng1 Nf6 $17 { We are ready to go d5 next. } ) 5... g4 ( 5... d6 { is also good } 6. d4 Bg7 7. d5 Ne5 8. gxf4 gxf4 9. Bxf4 Bg4 10. Be2 Nxf3+ 11. Bxf3 Qf6 12. O-O Bh3 13. Bg2 Bxg2 14. Kxg2 Qg6+ 15. Kh3 Bxc3 16. bxc3 O-O-O 17. Qg4+ Kb8 18. Rae1 Nf6 $15 ) 6. Nh4 Nd4 $5 { The knight is well placed here and we want to go d5 next bringing our bishop out. } 7. Nd5 { We have many promising ideas here. } 7... f3 ( 7... fxg3 8. hxg3 c6 9. Nf4 d5 10. c3 Ne6 11. d4 dxe4 12. Bc4 Ng5 $13 ) ( 7... Bd6 8. Qxg4 Be5 9. Qh5 ( 9. gxf4 d6 10. Nf5 Bxf5 11. exf5 Nf6 12. Nxf6+ Bxf6 $15 { The bishop is perfect on f6 here. } ) 9... d6 10. Nf3 Bg4 $1 { A very nice tactic to win the knight on f3. } 11. Qxg4 h5 12. Qh3 Nxf3+ 13. Ke2 Ng5 14. Qh4 f3+ 15. Ke1 Ne6 $11 { We trade the queens with a comfortable ending. } ) 8. c3 Ne6 { We have an extra pawn. } 9. h3 $1 { White has to try and break our bind on the queenside. } 9... h5 10. Nf5 ( 10. d4 c6 11. Ne3 Ng5 $15 { [%csl Re4] } ) 10... c6 11. Nde3 Ng5 12. hxg4 d5 $1 { We want to activate all our pieces. } 13. exd5 Bxf5 14. Nxf5 Qxd5 $11 { The position is complex but I would take Black any day with 0-0-0 coming up next. } *[Event "?"]
