1. e4 e5 2. d4 { We will continue looking at some early dubious lines, often involving gambits. It does break the general principles since White is not supposed to get his queen out so early. } ( 2. Nc3 Nf6 { We are actually not going for this move order in this database. I still feel its useful to see this line once as it might occur if you ever decide to go 2...Nf6 or if you mix up some move orders. } 3. d4 { This was played against me by a Serbian IM who was very well prepared. It has been played by Mamedyarov a few times. } 3... exd4 4. Qxd4 Nc6 5. Qd3 { This is the only move which is independent here. Others will likely transpose to the main line. } 5... Bc5 { This is the most ambitious move here. In my game, I went for the move d5 simplifying the game as I was outprepared. } ( 5... d5 6. Bf4 $1 { White is preparing to jump with Nb5 next after d4. } 6... Nb4 $5 ( 6... dxe4 7. Qxd8+ Nxd8 8. Bxc7 Nc6 { Black should be able to equalise here without too much trouble. } ) 7. Qd2 Nxe4 8. Nxe4 dxe4 9. Qxd8+ Kxd8 10. O-O-O+ Bd7 11. Bc4 Bd6 $11 { Black had equalised in the game 1/2-1/2 (48) Radovanovic,N (2422) -Arjun,K (2499) Belgrade 2022 } ) 6. Bf4 d6 7. Qd2 { White defends the pawn on f2 preparing to castle queenside. } ( 7. O-O-O { This is a pawn sacrifice but more likely just a bluff. I do not see the compensation. } 7... Bxf2 8. Nf3 O-O 9. Qe2 Bc5 10. Bg5 h6 11. Bh4 Bg4 $15 ) 7... Be6 8. O-O-O ( 8. Nf3 O-O 9. a3 a6 { We are ready to meet 0-0-0 with the move b5. } 10. O-O-O ( 10. Bd3 Ng4 $11 { [%cal Gc6e5] } ) 10... b5 11. e5 { White has to simplify here. } 11... dxe5 12. Nxe5 Qe8 13. Nxc6 Qxc6 14. Be2 Qxg2 { We take up the challenge, grabbing a couple of pawns. } 15. Rhg1 Qxf2 16. Bh6 Ng4 17. Ne4 Qh4 18. Nxc5 Nxh6 $11 { White has compensation for the pawns but we are not risking much here. } ) ( 8. a3 Qe7 $11 { [%cal Ge8c8] } ) 8... Bb4 $1 { We have to play concretely here exploiting our active pieces. } 9. Qd3 ( 9. Qe1 Qe7 { We are ready to castle queenside next. The a2 pawn also looks juicy. } 10. Bd2 O-O-O $11 ) ( 9. f3 { allows us to go } 9... Bxa2 10. Qe3 Be6 $15 ) 9... O-O 10. f3 Nd7 11. Kb1 b5 $1 { Our play is much easier on the queenside. } 12. Qe3 Rb8 $36 { We will continue with a5 next. } ) 2... exd4 3. Qxd4 { The only justification for White here is that he wants to castle queenside and so the queen comes out early. } ( 3. c3 { This is another classic gambit which has been played for a very long time. We have a very practical solution here. } 3... Qe7 { This is the easiest going after the e4 pawn. } 4. cxd4 { White gives up the e4 pawn but our queen is heading out pretty early. } ( 4. Bd3 d5 $1 5. cxd4 dxe4 6. Bc2 f5 $15 { We have a clean extra pawn here. } ) 4... Qxe4+ 5. Be3 ( 5. Be2 $2 Qxg2 6. Bf3 Qg6 $17 ) 5... Bb4+ 6. Nc3 Nf6 { We can go either Nd5 or Ng4 next. } 7. Nf3 ( 7. Qd2 Qc6 { Preparing Ne4 } 8. Rc1 O-O 9. Nge2 { It is going to take some time for White to complete his development. } 9... Ba5 { [%cal Gf6d5] } 10. a3 d5 $15 ) 7... Nd5 8. Qd2 Nxe3 { We win the bishop pair and also close the 'e' file. We can continue more slowly now. White has to prove his compensation. } 9. fxe3 Qe7 10. Bd3 d6 ( 10... d5 { is also fine. } 11. O-O Nd7 12. Rae1 ( 12. Nxd5 Bxd2 13. Nxe7 Bxe3+ 14. Kh1 Kxe7 15. Rae1 Kd6 16. Rxe3 Nf6 $11 ) 12... Nf6 13. e4 Nxe4 14. Bxe4 dxe4 15. Rxe4 Be6 ) 11. O-O Be6 12. e4 O-O 13. h3 f6 $11 { We have a solid position. We will continue with c6 and Nd7 next. } ) 3... Nc6 4. Qe3 { White keep the queen in the center and stops the immediate d5. He will look to castle queenside quickly. } ( 4. Qd3 { can be met with } 4... d5 ( 4... Bc5 $11 { is more complex } ) 5. Qxd5 Qxd5 6. exd5 Nb4 7. Bb5+ Bd7 8. Bxd7+ Kxd7 9. Kd1 Nxd5 $11 { We have a very comfortable endgame. } ) ( 4. Qc4 { The queen will come under fire here, after either the d5 break or just Be6. } 4... Nf6 5. Nc3 Bb4 6. Bd2 ( 6. Ne2 O-O 7. Bg5 h6 8. Bh4 Be7 9. Bg3 a6 $11 { We are ready to start playing on the queenside with b5 next. } ) 6... O-O 7. O-O-O Re8 8. f3 d6 { We are ready to go Be6 next. } 9. a3 a5 $15 { [%cal Gc8e6] White cannot take the bishop without allowing a dangerous attack on the queenside. } ) ( 4. Qa4 { The queen seems to be misplaced here. } 4... Bc5 5. Nf3 d6 6. Bg5 Ne7 7. Nc3 O-O ) 4... Nf6 5. Nc3 { This is the most common move but it allows us to go Bb4 and start putting pressure on the e4 pawn. } ( 5. Bd2 $5 { White tries to improve upon the mainline as Bb4 is not as effective here. } 5... Be7 { This is the simpler move here preparing to go d5 next. } ( 5... Bb4 { is also equal } 6. a3 Bxd2+ 7. Nxd2 O-O 8. O-O-O d5 9. exd5 Re8 10. Qb3 Qxd5 $11 ) 6. Nc3 d5 7. exd5 Nxd5 8. Nxd5 Qxd5 9. Ne2 { White needs to kick the queen away from d5 to castle. } 9... Bf5 10. Nc3 Qe5 11. O-O-O O-O-O $11 { We have the slight initiative in the endgame. } ) 5... Bb4 6. Bd2 O-O 7. O-O-O Re8 { So far all our moves have been very natural. White has a few options here. We are ready to go for the move d5 or take the pawn on e4 after Bxc3. } 8. Bc4 ( 8. f3 { runs into } 8... d5 9. Qf2 dxe4 10. Nxe4 Qe7 11. Nxf6+ Qxf6 $15 { We have a big lead in development and a safer king. } ) ( 8. Qf4 { White is ready to go f3 next. } 8... Bxc3 { Take any central pawn if it can be done without too much danger! } 9. Bxc3 Rxe4 10. Qg3 ( 10. Qd2 Re8 $15 { [%cal Gd7d6,Gf6e4] } ) 10... d5 11. f3 Re6 $1 { The rook keeps an eye on the f6 knight and we can also go Rd6 next followed by d4. } 12. Ne2 Rd6 13. Nd4 ( 13. Qf4 d4 $1 { We need the d5 square for the knight. } 14. Nxd4 Nd5 15. Nxc6 bxc6 $17 { Black was dominating in the game 0-1 (29) Nepomniachtchi,I (2751) -Anand,V (2783) Saint Louis 2017. } ) 13... Nxd4 14. Bxd4 Bf5 $15 { We can go for the move c5 next. } ) ( 8. Qg3 { This is the most played move in the position and is a pawn sacrifice. } 8... Nxe4 { Of course, we are going to take the bait. } 9. Nxe4 Rxe4 10. Bxb4 { The exchange of pieces is in our favour. } ( 10. Bf4 Qf6 $1 11. Bxc7 d6 $19 { We are dominating after Bf5 next. The rook can come to c8 and play along the 'c' file. } ) ( 10. c3 Be7 { White has no compensation here. } 11. Bd3 ( 11. Nf3 Ra4 $17 { [%cal Gd7d6,Gd6d5] } ) 11... Bh4 $1 { We are able to get our rook back to safety. } 12. Qf3 Re8 ) 10... Nxb4 ( 10... Rxb4 11. a3 Re4 { transposes. } ) 11. a3 Nc6 { White has not achieved anything with the move a3. } 12. Bd3 ( 12. Ne2 d6 13. Nc3 Re8 $17 ) 12... Re8 13. Nf3 d6 { We are just a clean pawn up here. } ) 8... d6 { We want to go Ne5 next and push the pawns on the queenside. } 9. Nf3 ( 9. f3 { allows us to go } 9... Ne5 10. Bb3 a5 11. a4 c6 $17 { We are going to open up the queenside with b5 next. } ) 9... Be6 { This is another typical plan to exchange White's defensive piece. } 10. Bxe6 ( 10. Bd3 Bc5 11. Qe2 Bg4 $15 { Either Nd4 or d5 is coming up next. } ) 10... Rxe6 11. Ng5 Re8 12. f3 Ne5 13. Qe2 h6 14. Nh3 c6 $15 { [%cal Gd6d5,Gb7b5, Ga7a5] Our play is much faster in the center and the queenside. } *[Event "?"]
