1. e4 e5 2. Bc4 { The Bishop's opening is more common than the lines we have seen so far. It is often also a weapon against Petroff players. Seeing that we are not going for the Petroff I don't mind allowing White to transpose back to an Italian. } 2... Nf6 3. d3 ( 3. d4 { This is a rare gambit line. } 3... exd4 4. Nf3 Bb4+ { We get our bishop out with a tempo. } 5. c3 { The principled continuation allowing us to trade the weak d4 pawn but White opens up the position with his lead in development. } ( 5. Bd2 Bxd2+ 6. Nbxd2 Nc6 $11 { White might be able to regain the pawn after some effort but we have no weaknesses in the position and are the ones playing for an advantage. } ) 5... dxc3 6. bxc3 ( 6. O-O { is too slow } 6... O-O 7. bxc3 Be7 $15 ) 6... d5 $5 { We give back the pawn but help bring our pieces out quickly. The pawn on d5 blocks the active bishop on c4. } ( 6... Be7 { allows } 7. e5 $16 ) 7. exd5 Be7 8. O-O O-O 9. Bb3 Bg4 $11 { We have a very comfortable position here with good chances to press. } ) ( 3. Nc3 Nc6 { White has to transpose here with the move d3. } 4. Nf3 { This is a well-known opening inaccuracy. } ( 4. f4 $2 { fails to } 4... Nxe4 $1 5. Nf3 Nxc3 6. dxc3 Qe7 $17 ) 4... Nxe4 $1 { We get rid of White's central pawn. } 5. Nxe4 ( 5. Bxf7+ $2 { Is really bad as the bishops and our center give us a huge advantage. } 5... Kxf7 6. Nxe4 d5 $19 ) 5... d5 6. Bd3 dxe4 7. Bxe4 Bd6 8. O-O O-O 9. Re1 { White keeps an eye on the e5 pawn. } ( 9. c3 f5 10. Bd5+ Kh8 11. d3 h6 $15 { We will go Qf6 and Ne7 next. We enjoy good control over the center. } ) 9... Bg4 10. c3 Kh8 11. h3 Bh5 { We are planning to go f5 next. White has to take on c6 at some point. } 12. Bxc6 bxc6 13. g4 Bg6 14. Nxe5 Bxe5 15. Rxe5 f5 $36 { [%cal Gd8h4] In opposite colour bishop positions king safety and activity are often more important compared to material. } ) 3... Nc6 4. Nc3 { White is preparing the move f4 and stops our plan of going d5. This is a more advanced version of the Vienna which we saw in the 2nd chapter. } ( 4. Nf3 { This would lead to our Italian lines after } 4... Bc5 $11 ) ( 4. a3 { This has been played a couple of times by Nabaty. Black can go } 4... d5 5. exd5 Nxd5 6. Nf3 Nb6 7. Bb3 Qf6 8. Nbd2 Be6 { We will castle queenside and start our play on the kingside. } 9. O-O O-O-O $11 ) 4... Bc5 { This is a simple move which keeps our play consistent with the Italian lines. We are also preparing a devious surprise for our opponent on the next move. } ( 4... Na5 { is a very logical response but we have to study these positions carefully. } ) 5. f4 { This is the most popular move. White often goes f5 next and starts playing on the kingside. } ( 5. Nge2 $2 { allows } 5... Ng4 $17 { [%cal Gd8h4] } ) ( 5. h3 { This has been played by some strong players in rapid and blitz. White is preparing to go Nge2 next. } 5... a6 $1 { We play a useful move creating a luft for the bishop. } 6. Nge2 ( 6. Nf3 { transposes to the Italian. } ) ( 6. a3 d6 7. Nge2 Be6 $11 ) 6... d6 7. O-O O-O 8. Kh1 Na5 { Finally we go after the bishop on c4 after we have done all the preparatory work for it. } 9. Bb3 Nxb3 10. axb3 d5 11. Bg5 dxe4 12. dxe4 Qxd1 13. Raxd1 Ne8 $11 { [%cal Gf7f6] We have the bishop pair and a comfortable endgame. } ) 5... h5 $5 { This is our surprise and a typical modern computer idea. We want to go Ng4 next and exploit the move f4. I have played this in a couple of games and my opponents typically collapse very quickly, partly in shock. Objectively it is just equal which makes it even better. } 6. Nf3 { White brings his knight out keeping an eye on the e5 pawn. } ( 6. fxe5 Ng4 7. Nh3 ( 7. Nf3 { It is not easy to go for this in a practical game giving up an exchange. This transposes to the main line. } ) 7... Ngxe5 $15 { We want to go d5 next and bring our bishop into the game. } ) ( 6. f5 { White attempts to keep the center under control and closes down the kingside but he has not stopped our idea. } 6... Ng4 $1 ( 6... d5 { This leads to a draw in most of the lines. } 7. Nxd5 ( 7. exd5 Nd4 $15 ) ( 7. Bxd5 Nxd5 8. Nxd5 Bxf5 $15 ) 7... Nxe4 8. dxe4 ( 8. Nxc7+ Qxc7 9. dxe4 b5 10. Bd5 Ba6 11. Nf3 Qb6 $11 ) 8... Qh4+ 9. Kd2 Bxf5 10. Nxc7+ ( 10. Bd3 Bxe4 11. Nxc7+ Kf8 12. Nf3 Qg4 $11 ) 10... Kf8 11. Nxa8 Qf4+ 12. Kc3 Qxe4 13. a4 Be6 14. Bxe6 Qb4+ 15. Kd3 Qd4+ 16. Ke2 Qf2+ $11 ) 7. Nh3 { White wants to go Ng5 next and so we go } 7... f6 $1 8. Na4 ( 8. a3 a5 $15 { This is a common reaction to a3 here. We gain space on the queenside. } ) 8... Qe7 { We would like to get our queen to c5 if we can. } 9. a3 a5 { We stop b4 and also create a square on a7 for the bishop. } 10. Bd2 Be3 11. Bxe3 Nxe3 12. Qd2 Nd4 $15 { The knights are dominating in the middle of the board. } ) ( 6. h3 { This would probably be my response in a game as White stopping Ng4 even though it does weaken the kingside. } 6... d5 $1 { Boom! We are not concerned with material here. We just want to keep playing energetically. } 7. exd5 Nxd5 $1 { We want to get our queen to h4. } 8. Nxd5 Be6 $1 { An important move- we do not rush with Qh4. Now the knight does not have a proper retreat. } 9. Qf3 { This is the most aggressive option giving up the rook on a1. } ( 9. Nxc7+ Qxc7 10. Bxe6 fxe6 $44 { We are ready to castle queenside with strong initiative. } ) ( 9. Be3 Bxe3 10. Nxe3 exf4 11. Nf1 { White's minor pieces are really ugly here. } 11... Bxc4 12. dxc4 Qh4+ 13. g3 fxg3 14. Qe2+ Kf8 $44 { We have more than enough pawns for the piece. } ) 9... Nd4 10. Qe4 Nxc2+ 11. Kd1 { The d3 pawn is an issue here. } ( 11. Kd2 { This keeps the pawn on d3 protected but it blocks the bishop on c1. } 11... Nxa1 12. Nf3 c6 13. Nc3 Bxc4 14. Qxc4 Be7 { We can afford to play a bit slowly here as it will take White some time to win back the exchange. } 15. fxe5 O-O 16. b3 b5 17. Qe4 f5 $1 18. Qxc6 ( 18. Qe3 Qb6 $11 ) 18... Rc8 19. Qxb5 Kh8 { We just get the king out of the way. } 20. Qa6 Bg5+ 21. Ke2 Be7 $11 { A strange repetition. } ) 11... Nxa1 12. Nf3 c6 13. Ne3 { White wants to bring his knight to c4. } ( 13. Nc3 { This is even simpler for us as we go } 13... Bxc4 14. Qxc4 O-O 15. Qxc5 Qxd3+ 16. Bd2 exf4 $44 { [%csl Rd1] } ) 13... Bxc4 14. Nxc4 Qd5 { We force the trade of queens. } 15. Qxe5+ Qxe5 16. fxe5 O-O-O 17. d4 b5 { We force the knight back to take on d4. Otherwise, Nd6 is an issue. } 18. Bd2 Bxd4 19. Nd6+ Rxd6 20. exd6 Bxb2 $11 ) 6... Ng4 { The standard reaction preparing to get the knight to f2. } 7. Qe2 { The natural move getting the queen away from the fork on f2. } ( 7. Rf1 { runs into } 7... Nxh2 $1 { A simple tactic forcing the rook back. } 8. Rh1 Nxf3+ 9. Qxf3 d5 $1 { Again we play energetically to bring the bishop into the game. } 10. Nxd5 Nd4 11. Qg3 Bg4 12. Ne3 f5 $1 { We defend the bishop on g4 and are planning to go Ne2 next. Otherwise, we would love to see the 'e' file opening up. } 13. Nxg4 ( 13. exf5 Qe7 $17 { [%cal Ge7e1] } ) 13... fxg4 14. Kd1 b5 { Now we go after the light-squared bishop. } 15. Bb3 a5 16. Be3 exf4 17. Qxf4 Nxb3 18. axb3 Bxe3 19. Qxe3 O-O 20. Ke2 g6 $11 { We reach an imbalanced endgame but it is objectively equal. Our kingside pawns can become pretty dangerous in the endgame. } ) ( 7. Ng5 Nf2 8. Bxf7+ { This is the better move order as White is not hit with the move d5. } ( 8. Qf3 d5 $1 { A very thematic move opening up the position for our pieces. The bishop is heading to g4. } 9. Bxd5 ( 9. exd5 Bg4 $17 ) 9... Nxh1 10. Be3 Nd4 11. Bxf7+ Kf8 12. O-O-O Be7 13. Bxd4 exd4 14. Bxh5 g6 $1 { A clever move preparing to go dxc3 followed by Qd4 defending the rook on h8. } ( 14... dxc3 15. Nf7 $13 ) 15. Nd5 gxh5 16. Rxh1 Rh6 $17 { We are up a whole rook and while White has some compensation with his active pieces it is not enough. } ) 8... Kf8 9. Qf3 Nxh1 10. Be3 Bxe3 11. Qxe3 Qf6 { [%cal Ge5f4] } 12. f5 { Nd5 is a big threat now. } 12... Nd4 13. Rc1 c6 $36 { [%cal Gd7d5] We cover the d5 square and are ready to go d5 next. We can also go Ke7 next followed by d6 and consolidate. We are up an exchange and White only has enough compensation to claim equality if he plays precisely. } ) ( 7. fxe5 { This is one of the critical lines as White fights back in the center giving up the rook on h1. } 7... Nf2 8. Qe2 Nxh1 9. Bg5 { White forces the bishop trade to get a few tempi for his pieces. } 9... Be7 10. Bxe7 Qxe7 11. Nd5 Qd8 12. O-O-O d6 { White wins the knight on h1 but we take the time to finish our development. The king will try to go to the queenside. } 13. exd6 Qxd6 14. e5 ( 14. Rxh1 Bg4 $15 ) 14... Qd8 15. Rxh1 Be6 16. Nf4 Bxc4 17. dxc4 Nd4 $11 { We trade another pair of minor pieces and White has to show his compensation in the resulting endgame. } ) 7... Nd4 { We trade one of the key defenders for White. } 8. Nxd4 exd4 9. Nd1 Qh4+ $1 { We would love to provoke the get the queen to h3 followed by h4 in the future. } 10. g3 ( 10. Kf1 Nxh2+ 11. Kg1 Qg4 $1 { We go after the knight on d1. White cannot decline the queen trade without losing it. } 12. Qf2 Qxd1+ 13. Kxh2 Qg4 $11 ) 10... Qh3 11. Bd2 ( 11. Qf1 { This has been played in two games but it just leads to a better endgame for us. } 11... Qxf1+ 12. Kxf1 h4 $15 { [%cal Gh4g3] 0-1 (57) Mammadova,G (2395) -Lagno,K (2550) Chess.com INT 2021 } ) 11... a5 { We stop the move b4 and gain space on the queenside. } 12. a3 c6 13. Ba2 d6 { We are ready to go h4 next. } 14. f5 Bd7 $36 { Now we will castle queenside and go for the g6 break. } *[Event "?"]
