1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 { This is the starting position of the Scotch but in this chapter, we take a look at a more aggressive version of the Italian. } ( 3. c3 { This is called the Ponziani variation and is one of the oldest chess openings having been advocated by Howard Staunton back in the 19th century. White is preparing to go d4 next. } 3... d5 4. Qa4 ( 4. exd5 Qxd5 $11 { Gives us a comfortable position with a big advantage in the center. } ) ( 4. Bb5 { Is a huge mistake } 4... dxe4 5. Nxe5 Qg5 $1 ( 5... Qd5 { Was played in the game 1/2-1/2 (31) Lu,S (2599) -Topalov,V (2813) Baku 2015. } ) 6. Qa4 Qxg2 7. Bxc6+ { Now the rook on h1 cannot be defended anymore as Rf1 will be met with Bh3. } ( 7. Rf1 Bd6 $1 8. Nxc6 a6 $1 9. Nd4+ axb5 10. Qxa8 Ne7 $19 { We are down a whole rook but our development advantage gives us a winning position. Look at his queenside. } ) 7... bxc6 8. Qxc6+ Kd8 9. Rf1 Bh3 10. Qxa8+ Ke7 $19 ) 4... Bd7 { We prepare to go Nd4 next move. We are trying to exploit the early Qa4. It does involve a pawn sacrifice. } ( 4... f6 { is also fine } ) 5. exd5 Nd4 6. Qd1 Nxf3+ 7. Qxf3 Nf6 { In return for the pawn we have a lead in development and the pawn on d5 is quite shaky. } 8. Bc4 ( 8. c4 { This weakens the d4 square. It also restricts the light-squares bishop and we will try to go for the c6 break soon. } 8... Bc5 9. Nc3 c6 10. h3 O-O 11. d3 cxd5 12. cxd5 Bd4 { We are going after the pawn on d5. } 13. Be2 Qa5 14. Bd2 Qb6 15. Rb1 Bxc3 { It is a concession to give up the bishop pair but we win d5 and our center will compensate for it. } 16. Bxc3 Qd6 17. O-O Rfe8 $11 ) 8... b5 $1 { We play concretely here to make use of our development advantage. } 9. Bb3 e4 10. Qe2 Bd6 { White cannot castle easily here as we can start our initiative on the kingside. } 11. d4 ( 11. O-O O-O { [%cal Gf6g4] } 12. h3 Qe8 $15 { The queen is heading to e5. } ) 11... O-O 12. Na3 ( 12. O-O $2 Ng4 $17 ) ( 12. Bg5 h6 13. Bh4 a5 { It is very useful to get the pawn to a4. } 14. O-O a4 15. Bc2 g5 16. Bg3 Bg4 $15 { [%csl Rd5][%cal Gf8e8] } ) 12... Rb8 13. Nc2 h6 14. h3 Qe8 15. O-O a5 { We go a5 after controlling the a4 square. } 16. a3 Nh7 17. f3 f5 18. fxe4 fxe4 19. Rxf8+ Qxf8 $44 { We have very good compensation with our bishop on d6. } ) 3... exd4 4. Bc4 { This is the only move order to get this position by force. We do not allow this via the Italian move order. However, both Nf6 and Bc5 here give White options to transpose back to the Italian. I will recommend an independent option. } 4... Bb4+ { This is a very provocative move as we end up opening the center for White's pieces. } ( 4... Bc5 { This fits with our repertoire against the Italian and we mainly have to study the move } 5. Ng5 { [%cal Gg5f7,Gd1h5] } ) 5. c3 dxc3 { There are three different options here- two recaptures and the principled move 0-0. } 6. O-O ( 6. bxc3 Ba5 7. O-O ( 7. Qb3 Qe7 8. O-O Nf6 $15 { We are going to castle next and White has no compensation. } ) 7... Bb6 $1 { This is an important move as the bishop was misplaced on a5. Our kingside is still not developed but we need only 2 moves to do so and White does not have anything immediately. } ( 7... Nge7 8. Ng5 Ne5 9. Bxf7+ Nxf7 10. Nxf7 Kxf7 11. Qh5+ $16 ) 8. Ba3 { The bishop looks good on this diagonal but it does not do much as we will go Ne7 followed by 0-0. } ( 8. e5 Nge7 9. Re1 d5 $1 10. exd6 Qxd6 $11 { We trade the queens here which should lead to a comfortable endgame for us. } ) 8... Nge7 9. e5 O-O 10. Re1 h6 { We play a useful move stopping Ng5. We will go Re8 and Ng6 next. } ( 10... Na5 { is another way to push the bishop back and to go Ng6. } 11. Bf1 Re8 $11 { [%cal Ge7g6,Gd7d5] } ) 11. Bb3 Re8 12. Nbd2 Na5 $1 { We want to push the bishop back before we go for the move d5. } 13. Bc2 ( 13. Nc4 Nxb3 14. axb3 Nc6 $11 ) 13... d5 14. exd6 cxd6 15. Ne4 Nc4 16. Bb3 $1 { White gives up the bishop to go after our pawn on f7. It only leads to a repetition after } 16... Nxa3 17. Nxd6 Rf8 18. Nxf7 Qxd1 19. Raxd1 Nc6 $1 { Nothing to be afraid of } 20. Rd6 Kh7 21. N7g5+ hxg5 22. Nxg5+ Kh8 23. Nf7+ Kh7 $11 ) ( 6. Nxc3 { This looks like the least threatening move to me but has been played by Firouza against Magnus in a blitz game. } 6... d6 7. O-O ( 7. Qb3 Bxc3+ 8. bxc3 Qe7 $15 { There is no compensation whatsoever for White. } ) ( 7. Ng5 Nh6 8. O-O O-O { We do not need to give up our bishop here. } 9. Nd5 Ne5 10. Be2 a5 $11 ) 7... Bxc3 { We get rid of the knight which was ready to jump to d5. The more trades the better for us. } 8. bxc3 Nf6 { The knight is best placed here fighting for the center. } ( 8... Be6 { Was played in 1/2-1/2 (69) Firouzja,A (2749) -Carlsen,M (2862) Lichess.org INT 2021 but it weakens the position after } 9. Bxe6 fxe6 10. Qb3 $36 { [%csl Rb7,Re6] } ) 9. e5 { This is the top engine move and the most common but it simplifies the position. } ( 9. Bg5 h6 10. Bh4 O-O $15 { We can go Be6 next. I do not see any compensation for White. } ) ( 9. Re1 O-O 10. h3 h6 11. Bf4 Nd7 $11 { Our knights can jump to different squares and it is not clear about our opponent's compensation. } ) 9... Nxe5 10. Nxe5 dxe5 11. Qxd8+ { This is the best here. } ( 11. Qb3 { This is the more common move according to the database but mostly in correspondence chess. Also, the games are pretty old. } 11... Qe7 12. Ba3 c5 13. Bb5+ Kf8 { The king is not doing too badly here. } 14. f4 ( 14. c4 Be6 15. f4 exf4 16. Rxf4 Rd8 $15 { We can bring our rook out with h5 and Rh6. } ) 14... exf4 15. Qc4 Qe3+ 16. Kh1 Kg8 17. Bxc5 Be6 $11 18. Qb4 a5 19. Qd4 Nd5 $15 { We will likely trade the queens soon and White has to be very accurate to hold the game. } ) 11... Kxd8 12. Bxf7 Ke7 13. Bb3 Be6 { We want to trade one of the bishops. We are still up a pawn. } 14. Re1 Bxb3 15. axb3 Ke6 $11 { White will probably win the pawn back but we are in no way worse. } ) 6... Nf6 $1 { We are not too worried about the move e5 since we can meet it with d5! It requires a lot of guts or good preparation to go for this on the board. } 7. e5 ( 7. bxc3 Bc5 8. e5 { is still met with } 8... d5 $1 9. exf6 dxc4 10. fxg7 Rg8 { White cannot do much without trading the queens } 11. Qxd8+ Nxd8 12. Re1+ Ne6 $11 ) 7... d5 $1 8. exf6 ( 8. Bb5 { Now that we have some control over the center we can be greedy. } 8... cxb2 9. Bxb2 Nd7 10. Qxd5 O-O { [%cal Gd7e5] } 11. Bxc6 bxc6 12. Qxc6 Rb8 $15 { [%cal Gc8b7] We have transformed our extra pawns into a double bishop advantage. } ) 8... dxc4 9. fxg7 Rg8 10. Qxd8+ Nxd8 11. Nxc3 Bxc3 12. bxc3 f6 { We create a safe square on f7 for the king. Our light squares are very secure and we are a pawn up once we win g7. } 13. Bh6 Kf7 14. Nd4 Kg6 15. Bf4 { So far all of this was played in the game 1/2-1/2 (21) Mastrovasilis,D (2587) -Vidit,S (2719) Baku 2023. Vidit could have done better with } 15... c5 16. Nb5 Ne6 17. Bg3 Bd7 18. Nd6 b6 $11 { We give up the c4 pawn but manage to coordinate our pieces. } *[Event "?"]
