1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Nxd4 { In modern times, the Scotch is getting more popular due to the huge amount of theory in the Ruy Lopez and now also in the Italian. It has been championed by players like Kasparov in the past. } 4... Nf6 { We go for the solid main line with Nf6. The other big direction is to go Bc5 but I have never really liked those positions. White gets the choice to choose the type of game he wants to get on the board. } 5. Nxc6 ( 5. Nc3 { will transpose to the Four Knights variation. } ) 5... bxc6 6. Bd3 { This is the second most played move here. White wants to castle as soon as he can but allows us to get control over the center. } ( 6. Qe2 { This is usually played after the inclusion of the moves e5 and Qe7. Her White goes Qe2 first and will meet Qe7 with Nc3. It has been played by Erigaisi in classical chess. } 6... Rb8 $5 { I like this move asking White to show us his plan. The rook is quite useful on the 'b' file. } ( 6... d5 { is a good option too. } 7. exd5+ Be7 8. dxc6 O-O $44 ) 7. e5 ( 7. Nd2 d5 $1 { We would love to open the center with the queen on e2. } 8. exd5+ $6 ( 8. Qe3 Be7 $11 { [%cal Ge8g8] } ) 8... Be7 9. dxc6 O-O $17 { [%cal Gf8e8] } ) 7... Nd5 8. c4 ( 8. g3 { is too slow } 8... Bc5 9. Bg2 O-O 10. O-O Re8 $11 { [%cal Gd7d6,Gc5d4] } ) ( 8. Nd2 { White is ready to meet Bc5 with Ne4. } 8... Be7 9. g3 O-O 10. Bg2 f6 $1 { We do not let White castle so easily. We want to get our bishop to f6 attacking b2. } 11. exf6 Bxf6 12. O-O { White gives up the pawn but it is not so straightforward. } 12... Bxb2 13. Bxd5+ cxd5 14. Rb1 Qf6 { Our pieces are in a bit of a bind but we will go Ba6 next and get our dark-squared bishop back. } 15. Qd3 Ba6 16. Qxd5+ Kh8 $36 { The long diagonal is a cause for concern for White. We have the bishop pair too. } ) 8... Bb4+ { This is the major advantage as compared to the main lines. The queen on e7 does not block the dark-squared bishop. } 9. Bd2 ( 9. Nd2 { This is pretty slow keeping the bishop on c1. } 9... Nf4 10. Qe3 Ne6 11. Bd3 d6 12. exd6 Bxd6 13. O-O O-O $11 { [%cal Gc6c5,Gc8b7] We can go c5 and get our bishop to b7. } ) 9... Nf4 10. Qe3 Ng6 { We keep an eye on the e5 pawn from here. } ( 10... Ne6 { was played by Levon } 11. Bxb4 Rxb4 12. b3 f6 13. Be2 fxe5 14. Qxe5 O-O 15. O-O d6 16. Qe3 { Was also okay for Black in the game 1/2-1/2 (55) Erigaisi,A (2727) -Aronian,L (2723) Chennai 2023 } 16... d5 $11 ) 11. Bd3 O-O 12. O-O a5 { We remove the pawn on a7 from attack and also defend b4. Now Bxb4 will be met with axb4 improving our pawn structure. } 13. f4 ( 13. Bxb4 axb4 14. Nd2 d6 15. exd6 cxd6 16. Rfe1 c5 $11 ) ( 13. a3 Bxd2 14. Nxd2 Re8 { White has to take on g6 at some point. } 15. Bxg6 ( 15. f4 d6 $11 ) 15... hxg6 16. Qc3 d6 17. exd6 cxd6 18. Rfe1 a4 $11 ) 13... d6 { We force White to trade on b4 as Bc5 is a huge threat. } 14. Bxb4 axb4 15. Nd2 dxe5 16. Bxg6 ( 16. fxe5 Nxe5 $15 ) 16... fxg6 17. fxe5 Rxf1+ 18. Rxf1 Be6 $11 { We can go Ra8 next and target the pawn on a2. } ) ( 6. Nd2 { This was introduced back to top-level chess by Vidit when he beat Tari with excellent prep back in 2022. } 6... Bc5 { This is the more fighting option getting the bishop out to its best square. } ( 6... d5 { This is the easiest option here to equalise but the game does simplify a lot. } 7. exd5 { This is the only way to keep some chances alive. } ( 7. Bd3 Bd6 $11 8. O-O O-O 9. h3 Re8 ) 7... cxd5 8. Bb5+ Bd7 9. Bxd7+ Qxd7 10. O-O Be7 11. b3 O-O 12. Bb2 Rfe8 ( 12... a5 13. a4 Qf5 14. Re1 { 1-0 (35) Vidit,S (2710) -Tari,A (2656) Mayrhofen 2022 } ) 13. Qf3 ( 13. Re1 h6 14. h3 c5 15. Nf3 ( 15. Qf3 Nh7 16. Rad1 Bf6 17. Bxf6 Nxf6 18. a4 Rad8 $11 ) 15... Qb7 16. Qd3 c4 17. Qf5 Ne4 18. Bd4 ( 18. Rad1 Bc5 19. Bd4 Bxd4 20. Nxd4 Nc3 $11 ) 18... Rac8 19. bxc4 Rxc4 20. Rab1 Qa8 $11 ) 13... Ng4 $1 { This is a very typical idea to prepare the move Bf6. } 14. h3 Bf6 15. Bxf6 Nxf6 16. Rfe1 Qd6 17. Qc3 c5 18. Nf3 h6 19. Rxe8+ Rxe8 20. Re1 Re4 $11 { 1/2-1/2 (64) Godena,M (2548) -Onischuk,A (2701) Reggio Emilia 2010 } ) 7. Bd3 ( 7. Be2 { This is pretty timid from White. } 7... d5 8. e5 ( 8. exd5 cxd5 9. Nb3 Bb6 $11 ) 8... Ng4 $1 9. Bxg4 Qh4 { We win the bishop pair and have good chances to create something on the kingside. } 10. O-O Bxg4 $15 ) ( 7. Nb3 { White gives up a pawn to win our bishop. } 7... Nxe4 8. Nxc5 Nxc5 9. Be3 Qe7 10. Qh5 d5 11. Be2 O-O 12. O-O Be6 13. Rfe1 Rfe8 14. Rad1 { This happened in the game 0-1 (45) Christiansen,J (2618) -Keymer,V (2738) Samarkand 2023. We have several different options. } 14... h6 $11 { [%cal Ga7a5,Ga5a4] } ) ( 7. e5 { The knight on d2 does not help much here. } 7... Qe7 8. Qe2 Nd5 9. Nb3 ( 9. Ne4 Bd4 10. f4 f5 $1 11. exf6 Nxf6 12. Nxf6+ Bxf6 $11 { Our bishop is very well placed on f6. } ) 9... Bb4+ 10. Kd1 { The king is not doing too badly here but combined with his lack of development he cannot fight for an advantage. } ( 10. c3 { allows us to go } 10... Nxc3 11. bxc3 Bxc3+ 12. Bd2 Bxa1 13. Nxa1 Qa3 $36 { We will likely win the pawn on a2 next. } ) 10... O-O ( 10... Bc3 { 0-1 (59) Aditya,M (2505) -Aradhya,G (2305) Chess.com INT 2023 } ) 11. c4 Nb6 12. a3 Bc5 13. Nxc5 Qxc5 14. Qe3 { All of these moves are forced for White to not get worse. } 14... Qe7 15. Bd3 f6 16. Qh3 g6 17. Qh4 Ba6 18. Re1 Rf7 $11 { We are ready to take on e5 next. I would definitely take Black here. } ) 7... O-O 8. O-O d5 { This is similar to the Four Knights Scotch but the knight is worse on d2 as compared to c3. } 9. h3 { White prepares to go e5 next. } ( 9. c4 Re8 10. Qc2 Qd6 $11 { We are planning to go Ng4 next. } ) ( 9. e5 Ng4 10. Nf3 f6 $1 { We would love to open the 'f' file with the pressure already on f2. } 11. e6 $1 { White gives up the pawn to keep the 'f' file closed for now. } ( 11. h3 $4 { runs into } 11... Nxf2 $1 12. Rxf2 Bxf2+ 13. Kxf2 fxe5 $19 ) 11... Qd6 12. h3 Ne5 13. Bf4 Bxe6 $11 { We can take on f3 and go Qd7 next. } ) 9... Qd6 { The queen stops e5 and also creates a big threat of Bxh3 followed by Qg3. } 10. Re1 ( 10. Nb3 dxe4 11. Nxc5 Qxc5 12. Be2 a5 $11 ) 10... Re8 11. Nb3 dxe4 12. Nxc5 Qxc5 13. Bf1 { White has some compensation with his bishop pair but at best for equality. } 13... a5 $11 { We want to go Qd6 next. It is important to stop the move b4 before we trade the queens. } ) 6... d5 7. exd5 ( 7. Qe2 { Is a very risky move going after our center leaving the king on e1. } 7... dxe4 8. Nc3 ( 8. Bxe4 Nxe4 9. Qxe4+ Qe7 $11 { The best White can hope for is equality in the endgame. } ) ( 8. Nd2 Bb4 9. Bxe4 O-O { The White king is in trouble here. } 10. c3 ( 10. Bxc6 $2 Bb7 $1 11. Bxb7 Re8 $19 ) 10... a5 $1 { We want to get our bishop to a6! } 11. cxb4 Ba6 12. Qe3 Re8 13. f3 Nd5 $36 { f5 is coming up next and we will at least win the piece back. } ) 8... Bb4 9. Bxe4 { White is playing a dangerous game here. } 9... O-O 10. Bxc6 Rb8 { The rook is coming into the game via b6. } 11. O-O Qd6 $1 12. Bb5 Ng4 13. g3 Bxc3 14. bxc3 Ne5 { We want to go Qd5 next and exploit the light-squares. } 15. Bf4 Rxb5 16. Qxb5 Nf3+ 17. Kg2 Qe6 $36 { [%cal Gf3h4,Gc8d7] We have excellent compensation here and White has to be very careful. } 18. Kxf3 { runs into } 18... Bd7 19. Qe5 Qc6+ 20. Ke3 Re8 $15 ) ( 7. e5 { is not great due to } 7... Ng4 8. O-O Bc5 { Qh4 is a huge threat now. } 9. Bf4 ( 9. h3 Nxe5 $15 ) ( 9. Qe2 Qe7 10. Bf4 g5 $1 { The standard reaction to Bf4 here. } 11. Bd2 Nxe5 12. Re1 Bd6 $15 ) 9... g5 $1 { We start our play quickly on the kingside. } 10. Bd2 ( 10. Bg3 $2 h5 $36 11. Be2 h4 12. Bxg4 hxg3 13. hxg3 Ke7 14. Qf3 Rh6 ) 10... O-O { [%csl Re5] } 11. b4 Bb6 { White has to play precisely here to equalise. } ( 11... Bd4 12. Bc3 Bxe5 $11 ) 12. a4 a5 13. bxa5 Bc5 14. Bc3 f6 $36 { We want to open the 'f' file. } ) 7... cxd5 8. O-O Be7 9. c4 { This is the only move which can justify White's play so far. He wants to get rid of our central pawn and play against the a7 and c7 pawns. } ( 9. Re1 O-O 10. h3 c5 $11 { We have a very comfortable position with the pawns on d5 and c5. } ) ( 9. Nc3 O-O 10. Bg5 ( 10. Bf4 c5 11. Re1 Be6 $11 { [%cal Ge7d6] } ) 10... Be6 11. Qf3 h6 12. Bf4 c5 $11 ) ( 9. h3 { This has been played several times by Jobava. Our plan is to castle and go c5 anyway. } 9... O-O 10. Nd2 c5 11. b3 Bb7 12. Re1 Qd7 $11 { We will bring our a8 rook to e8 and go Bd8 trading the rooks. } ) 9... d4 $1 { I like this move gaining space in the center. It is much more ambitious than allowing White to take our pawn on d5. White has to do something concrete here. } ( 9... O-O { is just equal. } 10. cxd5 Nxd5 ( 10... Bb7 $5 11. Nc3 Nxd5 12. Bd2 Nb4 13. Be4 Bxe4 14. Nxe4 Rb8 $11 ) 11. Qf3 ( 11. Be4 Be6 12. Qc2 h6 $11 13. Rd1 c6 14. Qxc6 Rc8 15. Qa4 ( 15. Qb5 Ne3 16. Re1 Ng4 ) 15... Nb6 16. Rxd8 Nxa4 17. Rxf8+ Kxf8 18. Nd2 Rd8 ) 11... Be6 12. Rd1 c6 13. h3 Qb8 14. Nd2 Qe5 $11 ) 10. Bg5 { White develops the bishop first before going Nd2. The bishop is not blocked on c1. } ( 10. Bf4 O-O 11. Nd2 Bb7 $11 { We will go c5 next. } ) ( 10. Nd2 { White wants to go Ne4 next. } 10... O-O 11. Ne4 ( 11. Nf3 c5 $15 ) ( 11. Re1 a5 { This is a typical move in these positions to go Ra6 next. } 12. Ne4 Nxe4 13. Bxe4 Ra6 $11 ) 11... Ng4 $5 { I like this idea of not trading the knights right away. We now want to go f5 and Ne5. White has to be careful not to get worse here. } 12. Bf4 { White tries to stop Ne5 but this allows us to go } ( 12. h3 Ne5 13. Bf4 Nxd3 14. Qxd3 a5 $11 { Black has a very comfortable position with the bishop pair. } ) ( 12. Re1 $6 f5 13. Nd2 Bh4 $1 14. g3 f4 $3 { We exploit our big lead in development. } 15. gxh4 Qxh4 16. Nf3 Qxf2+ 17. Kh1 Nxh2 $1 18. Nxh2 Bb7+ 19. Re4 Rae8 { 0-1 (27) Di Nicolantonio,L (2408) -Narayanan,S (2626) El Prat de Llobregat 2019 } ) ( 12. Ng3 Rb8 13. Nf5 Bxf5 14. Bxf5 Nf6 ) 12... f5 13. Ng3 g5 $1 { We need our knight on e5. } 14. Bd2 Ne5 15. Qc2 ( 15. Ba5 f4 16. Be4 fxg3 $1 { We give up the exchange for the initiative. } 17. Bxa8 Nxc4 $36 ) 15... Nxd3 16. Qxd3 f4 17. Ne4 a5 $11 { [%cal Ga8a6,Gc8b7,Gc7c5] We stop b4 and also prepare Ra6. We have a lot of play on the light squares. } ) 10... O-O 11. Nd2 a5 $5 { We have already seen this move a few times preparing to go Ra6. It is also useful to just gain space on the queenside. Nowadays with modern computers moves such as h5 and a5 are becoming common everywhere. } 12. Nb3 { White tries to go after our pawn on d4. We cannot play c5 as he then takes on f6. } ( 12. Qf3 Rb8 13. b3 h6 { The bishop is not able to retreat due to the queen on f3. } 14. Bh4 ( 14. Bxf6 Bxf6 15. Rae1 g6 $11 ) 14... Bg4 15. Qf4 Bd6 { The queen is trapped unless he goes } 16. Qxg4 Nxg4 17. Bxd8 Rbxd8 $15 ) ( 12. Re1 h6 13. Qe2 ( 13. Bxf6 { is never great. } 13... Bxf6 14. Qf3 Rb8 $11 ) ( 13. Bh4 Ra6 14. c5 Re6 $11 ) 13... Be6 14. Bxf6 Bxf6 15. Qh5 Bc8 $1 { White was threatening to take on e6. We do not need to do anything immediately. The bishop pair is a long-term trump for us. } 16. Ne4 Be7 17. Rad1 Ra6 $11 ) 12... a4 $1 13. Nxd4 Qxd4 { We did not blunder the queen :) We get three minor pieces in return which is more than sufficient compensation. } 14. Bxh7+ Nxh7 15. Qxd4 Nxg5 { White has to be extremely precise here to not get significantly worse. The three pieces are usually better in the middle game. } 16. b4 $1 { White forces us to simplify on the queenside. } ( 16. Rfe1 Ne6 $15 { [%cal Ga8a6,Ge7f6] } ) 16... axb3 ( 16... Bxb4 $4 17. c5 $18 ) 17. axb3 Rb8 $44 *[Event "?"]
