1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nxc6 bxc6 6. e5 Qe7 7. Qe2 Nd5 { We want to go g6 and Bg7 next targeting the pawn on e5. The most common try is c4 which we will check in the next chapter. Here we will focus on the trendy 8. h4 and some other sidelines. The sidelines are nothing much to worry about and all of them should transpose back to 8.c4 if White wants to fight for something. } 8. h4 { This has been the new trend in the Scotch for the last 5-8 years. Inspired by Alpha Zero, White advances his 'h' pawn. It can be useful in multiple ways- to gain space with h5, to go Bg5 or to get Rh3. } ( 8. b3 { White wants to meet Bg7 with the bishop on b2 but it weakens the dark squares. } 8... Qb4+ $1 9. Bd2 { We have forced the bishop to d2 after he played the move b3 intending Bb2. } 9... Qb6 { [%csl Gb2,Rd2][%cal Ga7a5,Gf8b4] } 10. a3 a5 { [%cal Gc8a6] } 11. c4 Qd4 12. Ra2 Nf4 13. Bxf4 Qxf4 $36 { We have managed to win the important dark-squared bishop. } ) ( 8. g3 { White wants to fianchetto the bishop but e5 is the problem. } 8... g6 9. Bg2 ( 9. c4 Ba6 { transposes to the next chapter. } ) 9... Bg7 10. O-O ( 10. f4 { Weakens the king too much. } 10... f6 11. exf6 Qxe2+ 12. Kxe2 Bxf6 $17 { We are ahead in development with a safer king. } ) 10... O-O 11. Re1 Re8 $15 { There is no easy way to defend e5. f4 is too weakening and if he goes c4 followed by Bf4, we can go g5 winning the pawn next. } ) ( 8. Nd2 { White brings the b1 knight to defend e5 when needed. } 8... g6 9. c4 { We would love to just transpose to the main line with Ba6 but we do not go for g6 in the Nd2 line there. But we do have several other options here. } ( 9. Ne4 Bg7 10. c4 Qb4+ { We force the king to stay in the center. } 11. Kd1 Nb6 12. b3 d5 $1 { We want to force White to open the long diagonal. } 13. exd6 O-O 14. Bb2 cxd6 15. Bxg7 Kxg7 16. Qd2 Qxd2+ 17. Kxd2 Rd8 { I prefer Black in this endgame with d5 coming next. } ) ( 9. Nf3 { This restricts the development of the f1 bishop. } 9... Bg7 10. b3 O-O 11. c4 Nb4 $15 ) 9... Nf4 10. Qe3 Ne6 { We keep our bishop on c8 for the moment and regroup our knight to e6 where it is better placed. } 11. b3 { Now, White wants to go Ne4 followed by Bb2 and Nf6 which is a serious threat. } ( 11. g3 c5 12. Bg2 Rb8 13. O-O Bg7 $11 { [%cal Ge6d4] The knight will go to d4 soon followed by the d6 break. } ) ( 11. Ne4 { is a pawn sacrifice but does not achieve much } 11... Bg7 12. Nf6+ Bxf6 13. exf6 Qxf6 14. Bd2 Qd4 $11 ) 11... f5 $1 { If the pawn is allowed to remain on f5 it becomes a big trump for us stopping Ne4. It also gains space on the kingside and for the king on f7. } 12. exf6 ( 12. Bb2 Qc5 { We will be happy to trade queens now. } 13. Qc3 Bb7 $11 { We have multiple plans here. We can castle long or we can go Qb4 followed by the move c5 activating the bishop on b7. } ) 12... Qxf6 13. Rb1 Qf7 { [%cal Gf8c5] We prepare both Bb4 and Bc5 depending on White's next move. I like such clever flexible moves. } ( 13... Bc5 { allows White to go } 14. Ne4 Bb4+ 15. Kd1 Qf5 $13 ) 14. Bd3 ( 14. Ne4 { allows } 14... Bb4+ 15. Bd2 Bxd2+ 16. Qxd2 O-O $11 { The White king is still stuck in the center. } ) 14... Bc5 15. Qf3 ( 15. Qg3 { allows at least a repetition after } 15... Bd6 $11 ) 15... O-O 16. O-O Qxf3 ( 16... Qg7 $11 ) 17. Nxf3 Nf4 { We win one of the bishops by force here. } 18. Bxf4 Rxf4 $11 { We have no issues with the bishop pair in this endgame. } ) 8... Qe6 { This is the easiest solution here in my opinion. We are ready now to go for the move d6 and we also open the diagonal for the f8 bishop. } 9. Nd2 { The knight is heading to f3. } ( 9. c4 Nb6 10. Nd2 a5 { transposes. } ) ( 9. h5 { This is too slow and does not achieve much. } 9... Be7 10. h6 g6 11. Nd2 O-O 12. Nf3 a5 $11 { This is a typical move here to prepare the move Ba6. } ) ( 9. g3 d6 { This is the simplest move trading the pawn on e5 and the queens most likely. } ( 9... Nb4 $11 ) 10. c4 ( 10. exd6 Bxd6 { [%csl Gd5,Gd6] There is a huge difference between the queen on e7 and e6. } 11. Qxe6+ Bxe6 $11 ) 10... Nb6 11. Bf4 ( 11. Bg2 { White sacrifices the pawn to complete his development quicker. } 11... dxe5 12. Nd2 Be7 13. O-O ( 13. b3 O-O 14. Bb2 f6 15. O-O { This happened in the game 1/2-1/2 (68) Bartel,M (2651) -Kozak, A (2578) Budva 2023. Black is doing great after } 15... a5 $11 { [%cal Ga5a4,Ge7b4] } ) 13... f6 14. Re1 Rb8 { We get the rook out of the way of a check on c6. } 15. Qh5+ Qf7 16. Bxc6+ Bd7 $11 ) ( 11. exd6 Bxd6 12. Be3 O-O 13. Nd2 { Black was just better in the game 1-0 (53) Nepomniachtchi,I (2732) -Kramnik,V (2808) Leuven 2017 after } 13... Re8 $15 { [%csl Re3][%cal Gd6g3] } ) 11... dxe5 12. Qxe5 Bb4+ 13. Nc3 Qxe5+ 14. Bxe5 O-O { White's king is still stuck in the center while we are ready to go Re8 next. } 15. O-O-O Re8 16. Bxc7 Bxc3 17. bxc3 Bg4 $11 { Black has excellent compensation for the pawn with Bf3 coming next. } ) 9... a5 $1 { We prepare the move Ba6. It is also useful to meet the move b3 with a4 on the queenside. } 10. g3 { White prepares the move Bh3. } ( 10. Qe4 { is met with } 10... Nb4 { We are threatening to go either f5 or d5. } 11. Kd1 { 1-0 (62) Ponkratov,P (2632) -Adhiban,B (2654) Moscow 2019 } 11... Bc5 $36 { [%csl Rd1,Rf2] } ) ( 10. Nf3 Bc5 { We stop the move Nd4. } 11. c4 Nb6 12. Bd2 d6 13. exd6 cxd6 $11 { We get a comfortable endgame. } ) ( 10. c4 Nb6 { The pawn on c4 is going to be an issue for White. } 11. Nf3 ( 11. h5 { is rarely a big concern for us. } 11... h6 12. g3 Bb4 13. a3 Be7 { We have provoked the move a3 and now we can meet b3 with a4 at the right moment. } 14. b3 a4 15. b4 O-O { [%cal Gc6c5,Gd7d5] } ) ( 11. g3 Bb4 12. a3 Bxd2+ 13. Bxd2 Ba6 $15 { The c4 pawn is in huge trouble here. } ) 11... Bb4+ 12. Bd2 Bxd2+ 13. Nxd2 { This is an unfortunate necessity to defend the c4 pawn. } 13... O-O 14. O-O-O { This was played in the game 1/2-1/2 (33) Nakamura,H (2787) -Robson,R (2660) Saint Louis 2018. I like the move } 14... a4 { We are preparing the move Ra5 attacking the e5 pawn. } 15. a3 Ra5 16. f4 d6 17. exd6 cxd6 18. Qxe6 Bxe6 $36 { White has to be precise as we are ready to go d5 next and his king is in trouble. } ) 10... Nb4 { We go after the c2 pawn and it also clears the d5 square for our queen. } ( 10... Nb6 { is also fine. } ) 11. Nf3 ( 11. Bh3 $2 Nxc2+ 12. Kd1 Qd5 $19 ) 11... Ba6 12. c4 Qg6 { [%cal Gb4c2] We want to force White to go Kd1 after which he cannot castle queenside. } 13. Kd1 { This was recommended by Sethuraman in his course on Chessable. There have been a few games played here since then and Black has a good score. } ( 13. h5 Qc2 14. Rh4 c5 { We create a square on c6 for the knight and also open the long diagonal for the bishop. } 15. a3 Qxe2+ 16. Kxe2 Nc6 17. h6 Rb8 18. Rb1 a4 $11 { We have a decent endgame here with our pressure along the 'b' file. } ) 13... c5 { We clear the c6 square for the knight. } 14. a3 ( 14. h5 Qb6 $15 { [%cal Ga6b7,Ge8c8] 1-0 (42) Parvanyan, A (2456) -Dragnev,V (2553) Sitges 2019 } ) 14... Nc6 15. h5 Qe6 16. Bd2 { The bishop is heading to c3 which seems like the best square. } ( 16. Bf4 { can be met with } 16... Nd4 17. Nxd4 cxd4 18. Qe4 Rb8 19. Qxd4 Qc6 20. Rh2 Bc5 { We get to activate our pieces in return for the pawn. } 21. Qc3 h6 22. Kc2 a4 23. e6 $1 { This is important to not get worse. } 23... dxe6 24. Qxg7 Ke7 25. Bg2 Qb6 26. Be5 Qb3+ 27. Kd2 Qxc4 { leads to a perpetual. } 28. Bf6+ Kd7 29. Qxf7+ Kc8 30. Bxh8 Qe2+ $11 ) 16... Be7 17. Bc3 O-O { We are ready to go d5 now with the king safe on g8. Also, Bb7 and Nd4 is an idea. } 18. Qe4 { White stops the move d5 but we can go } ( 18. Kc2 Bb7 $15 { [%cal Gc6d4,Rb7h1] } ) 18... f5 19. Qd5 Bb7 { We would like to go Nd8 and play along the long diagonal. } 20. Nd2 f4 { We would like to open the 'f' file for our rook. } 21. Bg2 Rab8 { We keep the bishop on b7 protected and prepare the move Nd4. } ( 21... Rf7 22. Qxe6 dxe6 23. Rf1 fxg3 24. fxg3 Rxf1+ 25. Bxf1 Nd4 26. Bxd4 cxd4 $11 ) 22. Rf1 Nd4 23. Qxe6+ dxe6 24. Bxb7 Rxb7 25. g4 Rd8 26.