1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nxc6 bxc6 6. e5 Qe7 7. Qe2 Nd5 8. c4 { This is the main line in the Scotch variation trying to kick the knight to a more passive square. It does weaken the queenside as we will try to go after it with Ba6 soon. } 8... Ba6 { There is no need to move the knight from d5. The usual plan here is to go g6 and Bg7 next. We have some other interesting plans though in the main lines. } 9. b3 ( 9. h4 { is met strongly with } 9... O-O-O 10. Rh3 Re8 11. f4 f6 12. Ra3 { The rook maneuvre looks very creative but we are just better after } 12... Qb4+ 13. Kd1 Bxc4 14. Qxc4 Qxc4 15. Bxc4 Bxa3 $15 ) ( 9. f4 g5 10. fxg5 { This was not great for White in the game 1/2-1/2 (43) Nepomniachtchi,I (2771) -Firouzja,A (2777) Saint Louis 2023 } 10... O-O-O $15 ) ( 9. Qe4 { Is a weird move as we can repeat moves with Nf6 back. We can also play for the advantage with } 9... Nb4 { [%cal Gd7d5] } 10. Nc3 Rd8 { d5 is hard to stop here. } 11. Kd1 $1 ( 11. Bf4 d5 $17 ) ( 11. c5 Bxf1 12. Kxf1 Qxc5 13. Be3 Qa5 $15 { [%cal Gb4d5] } ) 11... d5 12. exd6 Rxd6+ 13. Bd2 Re6 14. Qf3 c5 $11 { Our king is safer and our rook is very active on e6. The position is dynamically balanced. } ) ( 9. g3 { This is an annoying move order for us as we have to go for the move g6. But we still have our twists here. } 9... g6 { We are quickly going after the pawn on e5. } 10. b3 { White gets his bishop to b2 to keep the e5 pawn defended. But this does sacrifice his development on the kingside. } ( 10. Bg2 { This does not give White enough time to defend the e5 pawn with his dark-squared bishop. } 10... Bg7 11. O-O O-O 12. Re1 ( 12. Nd2 Nb6 $11 ) 12... Rfe8 13. Qc2 Qc5 { White cannot defend e5 anymore. The engine claims he has some compensation but it is not so easy practically. } 14. Nd2 Rxe5 15. Rxe5 Bxe5 16. Bf1 Nb6 $11 ) 10... Bg7 11. Bb2 O-O-O $5 { This is a relatively new idea but it has been played by a few strong people. I want to keep the king active in the endgame on the queenside. } ( 11... O-O { This is the big main line here. } 12. Bg2 Rae8 13. O-O Bxe5 14. Bxe5 Qxe5 15. Qxe5 Rxe5 $11 { If we compare this position to our main line, I would definitely prefer to have my king on c8 closer to my pawns. } ) 12. Bg2 { This is the usual line here. } ( 12. Nd2 { This is rarer but White is planning to go 0-0-0 which can be an issue. } 12... d6 { We have to immediately fight back in the center. } 13. Bh3+ ( 13. Qe4 Nb6 14. c5 Bxf1 15. cxb6 Ba6 { The king on e1 is a big concern for White. } 16. Qxc6 Bxe5 17. Qxc7+ Qxc7 18. bxc7 Rde8 $11 { Our bishop is a better minor piece in these complex endgames. } ) 13... Kb8 14. Nf3 dxe5 15. O-O { White gave up the pawn on e5 but now suddenly our king is weaker on the queenside. } 15... Rhe8 16. Rfd1 f5 { e4 is a big threat now. } 17. Qe1 $1 e4 ( 17... Nb4 { is also possible } 18. Rxd8+ Rxd8 19. Nxe5 Kc8 $1 20. a3 Nc2 21. Qa5 Bb7 22. Rc1 Bxe5 23. Qxe5 Qxe5 24. Bxe5 Nd4 25. Bxd4 Rxd4 $11 { [%csl Ra3, Rb3][%cal Gd4d3] } ) 18. Bxg7 exf3 { We simplify the position going into an endgame. } ( 18... Qxg7 19. Nd4 $13 ) 19. Qxe7 Nxe7 20. Rxd8+ Rxd8 21. Bf6 Rd7 22. Re1 Nc8 { We have an extra pawn on f3 which restricts our opponent's king. However, the bishop pair and the bishop stuck on a6 give White enough compensation. } 23. g4 c5 $11 { [%cal Ga6b7] } ) 12... Rde8 { White cannot defend the e5 pawn anymore. } 13. O-O ( 13. Qd2 $14 { White tries to get away from the queen trade at the cost of a tempo. } 13... Bxe5 14. O-O Bxb2 15. Qxb2 Qf6 16. Qa3 Bb7 17. Nd2 Nc3 18. Qxa7 Qd4 $1 { We find a nice tactical way to force the trade and we reach a comfortable endgame. } 19. Qxd4 Ne2+ $11 ) 13... Bxe5 14. Qxe5 Qxe5 15. Bxe5 Rxe5 { The same position is reached in the main lines with the king on g8. I like our king here as we have our pawn majority in the center. } 16. cxd5 Bxf1 17. Kxf1 cxd5 18. f4 { This is a difference here with the king on c8. } ( 18. Nc3 { This gives us better chances here. } 18... c6 19. Rc1 Kb8 20