 here to prove his compensation for the pawn. Our only issue is the bishop on a6. } ) ( 11. Bb2 { This is the 2nd most played move here but a slight inaccuracy. } 11... fxe5 { White cannot win the pawn back anytime soon. He has to show his compensation. } 12. O-O-O Re8 13. g3 Nf6 14. Bg2 $1 { is probably the better move. } ( 14. Bh3 Kb8 15. Rhe1 e4 16. f3 e3 17. Nf1 Qf7 $15 { White does not have enough for the pawn here. We will continue with either Bc5 or Qh5 next. } ) 14... e4 { [%cal Gd7d5] } 15. Qe3 Kb8 16. Rhe1 d5 17. f3 $1 { White is able to simplify the position. } 17... exf3 18. Qxe7 Bxe7 19. Nxf3 Bb4 $36 { We have definite pressure in the endgame. } ) 11... Nb4 { This is more risky as the knight has no squares but it also creates the most threats in White's position. Nc2 is currently a threat. } 12. Bb2 Bb7 { We are ready to go c5 next. } 13. exf6 gxf6 14. Qxe7 Bxe7 15. Kd1 { Now the threat is to go a3 and kick our knight back. } 15... c5 16. a3 Nc6 17. Be2 ( 17. Kc2 Nd4+ 18. Bxd4 cxd4 19. Rg1 a5 $11 { The endgame is balanced as White will go Be2-f3 next and trade the light-squared bishops. } ) 17... Rhf8 { We want to go f5 followed by Bf6 next. After the trade of dark-squared bishops, we get the d4 square for the knight. } 18. Kc2 f5 19. Rhe1 Bf6 $11 ) 9... Qh4 $5 { We want to go Qd4 or Bb4 if given the chance. We can also go Nf4-g6 regrouping the knight with a tempo. } ( 9... g6 { This is by far the main move here but White has several options which have been analysed deeply. White can at least force a draw in many lines. } ) 10. a3 { White stops the move Bb4 and creates a square on a2 for the rook. } ( 10. Bb2 { allows us to go } 10... Bb4+ $1 11. Nd2 ( 11. Kd1 Nf4 12. Qe4 ( 12. g3 $5 { White weakens his pawn structure but forces the trade of queens. } 12... Nxe2 13. gxh4 Nf4 $11 ) ( 12. Qf3 Ne6 $11 { The knight is well placed on e6. White has to be careful with the king on d1. } ) 12... Bb7 13. g3 Qh5+ 14. Kc2 Nh3 15. Bxh3 Qxh3 $36 { We have the bishop pair and the safer king. The king will castle queenside next. } ) 11... Nc3 { We want to get the knight to e4 next using the pin along the e1-a5 diagonal. } 12. Qe3 ( 12. Bxc3 { is not great giving up the bishop so easily. } 12... Bxc3 13. O-O-O Qe7 { The queen is heading to a3 now. } 14. Kb1 Bb7 $36 { We are ready to go a5-a4 next. } ) 12... Ne4 13. g3 { We have a choice here whether to go into an endgame or to keep the queens on the board. } ( 13. Bc1 $2 f5 $19 { We cement the knight on e4 and can meet g3 with Qe7-e5. } ) 13... Qh6 { I like this option the most here. We trade the queens but keep the pin alive. } ( 13... Qg4 { keeps the queens on the board for now. } 14. f3 Bxd2+ 15. Qxd2 Qxf3 16. Qg2 Ng5 17. Qxf3 Nxf3+ 18. Ke2 Ng5 19. h4 Ne6 $11 ) ( 13... Bxd2+ { is also equal but gives White some play. } 14. Qxd2 Nxd2 15. gxh4 Nf3+ 16. Ke2 Nxh4 17. f4 $13 ) 14. Qxh6 gxh6 15. Bc1 d5 $1 { We would love to open the 'd' file. } 16. exd6 ( 16. f3 Nc5 17. Kf2 Bc3 $11 { [%cal Gc3e5] We win the pawn on e5 with a comfortable endgame. } ) 16... O-O-O 17. Bh3+ Kb8 18. d7 { White has managed to keep the 'd' file closed for now but he allows us to go } 18... Ng5 $1 19. Bf5 Nf3+ 20. Kf1 ( 20. Kd1 Nd4 21. Bh3 f5 $11 { The 'd' file continues to remain an issue for White. } ) 20... Nxd2+ 21. Ke2 Nxc4 22. bxc4 Bxc4+ 23. Ke3 Bc5+ $11 { We will go Be6 next and win the pawn on d7. The endgame is equal. } ) 10... Nf4 11. Qe4 ( 11. Qe3 Ne6 $11 { Bc5 is coming up next. } ) 11... Ng6 { We are forced to trade the queens here. } 12. Qxh4 ( 12. Qe3 { does not make much sense as he wastes further time instead of developing his pieces. } 12... c5 13. Bb2 ( 13. Nc3 O-O-O { [%cal Gd8e8,Ge8e1] } 14. Bb2 Re8 15. O-O-O Rxe5 16. Qd2 Qf4 $11 { We have won a pawn and will trade the queens now in time. } ) 13... Qf4 { We force the trade here and f4 is a better square for the knight. } 14. Qxf4 Nxf4 15. Nc3 Rb8 { The drawback of a3 is that the b3 pawn is quite weak. } 16. O-O-O Rxb3 17. Nb5 { Our rook on b3 is stuck but we will give up the rook on b2 for the important dark-squared bishop. } 17... Kd8 18. Kc2 Rxb2+ 19. Kxb2 g5 $1 { A nice move gaining space on the kingside and stopping the plan of g3, f4. } 20. Nxa7 Bg7 21. Nc6+ Kc8 22. Ne7+ Kd8 23. Nf5 Bxe5+ 24. Kc2 Bb7 25. f3 Bf6 $44 { We have excellent compensation with the bishop pair here. d4 is an outpost for us. } ) 12... Nxh4 13. Bb2 { This is more flexible, keeping the option to go either Nd2 or Nc3 open. } ( 13. Nd2 { Once the knight is committed to d2 we can go for } 13... c5 14. Bb2 Bb7 15. Rg1 a5 16. Bc3 Be7 17. O-O-O Nf5 { The knight will land on d4 next with a comfortable position. } 18. Kb2 Nd4 $11 ) 13... Bb7 ( 13... c5 { allows } 14. Nc3 $14 ) 14. Nc3 { Now the knight is ready to jump to d5/b5 and so we will keep our pawn on c6 for the time being. } ( 14. Rg1 { is pretty slow and we can go } 14... Be7 15. Nc3 f6 { We are in time to break in the center. } 16. exf6 Bxf6 17. O-O-O c5 $11 ) 14... O-O-O 15. O-O-O ( 15. f4 d6 { Now White cannot take on d6 with the king still on e1. } 16. O-O-O dxe5 17. Rxd8+ Kxd8 18. fxe5 Be7 19. Be2 Nxg2 20. Rd1+ Ke8 21. Bf3 Nf4 $11 { We will activate our rook with h5 and Rh6. Keep in mind that we cannot castle kingside anymore :) } ) 15... Ng6 16. Re1 ( 16. Ne4 Re8 { White cannot defend the pawn on e5 anymore. } 17. c5 Nxe5 18. b4 f5 19. Nd2 Ng4 20. Bd4 Be7 $11 { We will go Bf6 next and trade the bishops. } ) 16... Re8 17. g3 { White cannot defend the pawn but he does have some initiative with his active pieces. The pawn on g3 restricts our knight. } ( 17. h4 { White wants to go h5 and kick the knight from the ideal g6 square. } 17... Rxe5 18. Ne4 Re6 19. h5 c5 20. hxg6 Bxe4 21. gxf7 h5 $11 { [%cal Ge4g6] } ) 17... Rxe5 18. Bd3 ( 18. Bg2 c5 19. Nd5 Rxe1+ 20. Rxe1 Kd8 $11 ) 18... Re6 { This is a clever move provoking the move Bf5. Let us see the reason why. } ( 18... Rxe1+ 19. Rxe1 Kd8 20. Ne4 h6 21. f4 $16 ) 19. Bf5 ( 19. Rxe6 { is a favourable trade for us opening the 'f' file. } 19... fxe6 20. Ne4 c5 21. Re1 Bxe4 22. Bxe4 Ne7 23. Re3 h5 $11 { [%cal Gh5h4] } ) 19... Rxe1+ 20. Rxe1 Kd8 21. Ne4 { This was much more dangerous with the bishop on d3 as White could go f4-f6. Now we will be able to get the move Ne7 with a tempo. } 21... h6 22. b4 Bc8 { We want to d6 and trade the bishops next. } 23. Nd2 ( 23. Nc5 Bxc5 24. bxc5 Rg8 $11 { d5 is coming up next. } ) 23... Ne7 24. Be4 d6 $11 { [%cal Gc8f5,Gc8e6] We get the bishop out next and White has to work hard to show his compensation for the pawn. } *[Event "?"]
