1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6 { The Four Knights variation is very popular among club players and it is often the first opening they play. It follows the general rule to develop the knights before the bishops. There are a few players who play this ambitiously with White but also a bunch of players who want to be very solid. We will try to find the balance between playing "correct chess" and trying to get a fighting game. In this chapter, we will see a bunch of random moves here. We will usually go d5 if given the chance. } 4. g3 { This is a worse cousin of the 2.Nc3 and 3.g3 variation. The knight on f3 is not doing so well in these positions. } ( 4. Bc4 { was analysed in the Bishop's opening. } ) ( 4. Nxe5 $6 { is a bullet opening and is of course bad objectively. } 4... Nxe5 5. d4 Ng6 6. e5 Ng8 $19 { [%cal Gd7d6,Gd6d5] } ) ( 4. h3 { There are a bunch of moves like this where White allows us to go for the d5 break and claims that the move h3 changes the evaluation in his favour. I do not believe it does and I think it is the easiest solution to our opening problems. } 4... d5 5. exd5 Nxd5 6. Bb5 Nxc3 7. bxc3 Bd6 { White usually gets this exact position from the opposite side in the 4.d4 variation without the move h6/h3. It helps White but does not change the evaluation drastically. } 8. O-O O-O 9. d4 ( 9. Re1 Bf5 { This is usually the best square for the bishop in these lines. } 10. Bxc6 bxc6 11. Nxe5 Re8 12. Nc4 ( 12. Nxc6 $6 { this is too greedy } 12... Qd7 13. Nd4 Bxh3 $15 ) 12... Rxe1+ 13. Qxe1 Bxc2 $11 { We win back the pawn with an equal position. } ) 9... exd4 10. cxd4 Bf5 { As I mentioned this is the ideal square for the bishop. } 11. c4 ( 11. Bg5 Qc8 12. Re1 a6 13. Ba4 b5 { We are going after the light-squared bishop. } 14. Bb3 Na5 $11 ) ( 11. Re1 h6 { We stop ideas of Bg5 and create a luft on h7. } 12. Bd3 Qd7 13. c4 Rfe8 $11 ) 11... h6 { This is always a useful move and we want to go Qf6 next. White cannot advance his pawns easily as it will likely create a lot of weaknesses. } 12. Bb2 Nb4 { I like this move utilising the weaknesses in White's position. } 13. Bc3 Nc2 14. c5 ( 14. Rc1 Na3 $15 { [%csl Rb5,Rc4] this is surprisingly bad for White. } ) 14... Bf4 15. d5 c6 $1 16. Ba4 Nxa1 $11 { White gets some compensation after the move d6 but it is at best enough for equality. } ) ( 4. Be2 { is also met with } 4... d5 5. exd5 Nxd5 6. O-O Nxc3 7. bxc3 e4 { This is a better version for us as the knight is forced to go back. The bishop would much rather be on b5 in these lines. } 8. Ne1 ( 8. Nd4 Nxd4 9. cxd4 Qxd4 10. c3 Qd5 $36 { We will continue with Bd6 and Bf5 in the center. } ) 8... Bd6 9. f3 Bf5 10. fxe4 Bxe4 11. Nf3 O-O 12. d3 Bg6 $15 { We have the better pawn structure and the more active pieces. } ) ( 4. a4 d5 { This is not an exception to our plan. } 5. exd5 ( 5. Bb5 Nxe4 $1 6. Nxe5 Qf6 7. Nf3 Be6 8. O-O Bd6 9. Re1 O-O { We give up the pawn in return for development. } 10. Nxe4 dxe4 11. Rxe4 Bd5 12. Re3 a6 13. Bxc6 bxc6 $44 { We have excellent compensation with the two bishops in the middle of the board. } ) 5... Nxd5 6. Bb5 Nxc3 7. bxc3 Bd6 8. O-O O-O 9. d4 exd4 10. cxd4 Bf5 { We prepare the move Nb4. } 11. Re1 ( 11. c3 Na5 { We can go c5 next and play against White's pawns in the center which may become a weakness. } ) 11... Nb4 $1 { This is the benefit of having the bishop on this diagonal. } 12. Bg5 Bxc2 13. Bxd8 Bxd1 14. Bxc7 Bxc7 15. Raxd1 g6 $11 { The endgame is equal with opposite colour bishops. } ) ( 4. a3 { This has been played by Magnus but I again do not see why we need to deviate from our plan. } 4... d5 5. Bb5 { As we saw before this is met with } ( 5. exd5 Nxd5 6. Bb5 ( 6. Nxe5 { is a try but does not lead to much after } 6... Nxe5 7. Qe2 f6 8. d4 Nxc3 9. bxc3 Qd5 10. dxe5 fxe5 $11 { We have nothing to worry about here. } ) 6... Nxc3 7. bxc3 Bd6 8. d4 exd4 9. cxd4 O-O 10. O-O { a3 is not that useful in these lines. It may help stop the plan of Bf5 and Nb4 but instead we go } 10... Bg4 11. c3 Qf6 $11 { White gets the same position in the main lines with the pawn on a2. We are definitely not worse here. } ) 5... Nxe4 $1 { We remove the knight to go either Qf6 or Qg5 when White takes on e5. } 6. Qe2 ( 6. Nxe5 $6 { is met strongly with } 6... Qg5 $1 7. Nxc6 Qxg2 8. Rf1 a6 { We get back the piece at minimum. } 9. Nxd5 ( 9. Ba4 Nxc3 10. dxc3 Qe4+ 11. Qe2 Qxe2+ 12. Kxe2 Bd7 $17 ) 9... axb5 10. Nxc7+ Kd7 11. Nxa8 Kxc6 { [%cal Gc8g4] The king looks weak on c6 but there is no way White can exploit it and we want to bring the rook to e8 as quickly as we can. } 12. Qe2 { This happened in the game 0-1 (31) Safarli,E (2607) -Esipenko,A (2683) Baku 2023. Black is much better after } 12... Bc5 $15 ) 6... Qd6 { We keep an eye on the e5 pawn. We would like to go Bd7 followed by 0-0-0 in these lines. } 7. Nxe4 ( 7. Nxd5 Qxd5 8. Bc4 Qd6 { The bishop is better on b5 in these lines indirectly targeting the e5 pawn. } 9. Qxe4 Be7 10. d3 Be6 $11 ) 7... dxe4 8. Qxe4 Bd7 { 0-0-0 is coming up next. White has to be careful to equalise here. } 9. d4 $1 ( 9. O-O O-O-O $15 { [%cal Gf7f5] } ) 9... O-O-O ( 9... f5 { is an interesting option which you can explore. } 10. Qe2 e4 11. Bxc6 Bxc6 12. Ne5 Be7 13. Bg5 ( 13. Bf4 O-O 14. O-O-O Qe6 15. Kb1 Be8 $11 ) 13... Qxd4 14. Qh5+ g6 15. Nxg6 hxg6 16. Qxg6+ Kf8 17. Qxf5+ Ke8 18. Qg6+ Kf8 $11 ) 10. dxe5 { This forces us to simplify the position. } 10... Nxe5 11. Bxd7+ Qxd7 12. Be3 ( 12. O-O Nxf3+ 13. Qxf3 Bc5 $11 { Our king is pretty safe on the queenside. Our pieces are also well placed in the center. } ) 12... Nxf3+ 13. Qxf3 Qd5 $11 { We reach an endgame which is completely equal. } ) 4... Bc5 { We deviate from our usual plan of going d5 because this gives us more chances to outplay our opponent. With the bishop on g2 it makes sense not to open up the center so quickly. } ( 4... d5 { is certainly possible here and I will give some of my analysis. I just feel that Bc5 is more ambitious here. } 5. exd5 Nxd5 6. Bg2 Nxc3 7. bxc3 Bc5 8. O-O O-O 9. Re1 ( 9. Nxe5 Nxe5 10. d4 Bd6 ( 10... Qf6 $11 ) 11. dxe5 Bxe5 $11 ) ( 9. d3 f6 { [%cal Gc8e6] } ( 9... Bg4 10. h3 Bh5 11. g4 Bg6 12. Ng5 Be7 13. Ne4 f5 14. gxf5 Bxf5 15. Rb1 Rb8 16. f4 Qd7 $11 ) 10. Nd2 ( 10. Re1 Bg4 11. h3 Bh5 $11 ) ( 10. Rb1 Be6 11. Rxb7 Bb6 12. Nd4 Nxd4 13. cxd4 exd4 $15 ) 10... Be6 11. Ne4 ( 11. Nb3 Bd6 $1 ) 11... Be7 $11 ) 9... h6 $5 10. Rb1 ( 10. d3 Re8 $11 ) 10... Bb6 11. d3 Re8 12. Be3 Ba5 13. Bd2 Bb6 14. a4 { 0-1 (59) Nakamura,H (2736) -So,W (2765) chess.com INT 2020 } 14... Bg4 $11 ) 5. Bg2 ( 5. Nxe5 $4 { does not work } 5... Nxe5 6. d4 Bxd4 $19 { [%csl Rd4,Re1][%cal Ge5f3] } ) 5... d6 6. O-O ( 6. d3 a5 { We make sure White cannot go for the move Na4 and win our bishop. } 7. Be3 { This is common in the Italian lines and we almost always take on e3. This is a similar situation here. } 7... Bxe3 8. fxe3 O-O 9. d4 Re8 $15 { [%cal Gb7b6,Gc8a6] } ) 6... O-O 7. d3 a5 { We always prefer the move a5 over a6 as it gains more space on the queenside. } 8. h3 ( 8. Be3 Bxe3 9. fxe3 Ne7 10. Nh4 c6 $15 { The bishop is completely stuck on g2 here. We can go Be6 followed by the d5 break. } ) ( 8. Bg5 { does not achieve much } 8... h6 9. Bh4 ( 9. Bxf6 Qxf6 $11 ) 9... Bg4 { Now the move g5 is a big threat. } 10. Bxf6 Qxf6 11. Nd5 Qd8 12. h3 Be6 $11 ) 8... a4 { We gain even more space on the queenside. I want to see White creating something on the kingside. It is more likely to create some weaknesses rather than a dangerous attack. } 9. a3 ( 9. Kh2 h6 10. Nh4 Nd4 $15 { We can continue with c6 and b5 next. } ) 9... h6 10. Kh2 Re8 { We will keep continuing normally with Be6 and Ne7 next. } 11. Nh4 Nd4 { This makes a lot of sense once White removes his knight from f3. } 12. Be3 ( 12. f4 $2 { does not work yet. } 12... exf4 13. gxf4 Nxe4 $17 ) 12... c6 13. Re1 b5 14. Ne2 Nxe2 15. Qxe2 Bxe3 16. Qxe3 c5 $15 { We have clear play on the queenside and the better minor piece. White has to start defending here. } *[Event "?"]
