1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. d4 { I call this the Four Knight Scotch and it is a pretty annoying line as White is very solid. He can also do this via the Scotch move order but it gives us more options. } 4... exd4 5. Nxd4 { Here I was trying to choose between two options- the big main line with Bb4 or to go for the Nxe4 line which is more likely to surprise our opponent. But the drawback there was that White has a few options to force a draw and some which are pretty critical. I did not see its benefit and I want something which we can play for a long time. } ( 5. Nd5 { This is the Belgrade gambit but Black has a well-known refutation. } 5... Nb4 $1 { White cannot keep his knight on d5 for long. } 6. Nxf6+ ( 6. Nxd4 $6 { White gives us a pawn but does not get enough compensation in return. } 6... Nbxd5 7. exd5 Nxd5 8. Nf5 ( 8. c3 Nf6 $15 ) 8... Ne7 $17 { We will go d5 next with a clean extra pawn. } ) ( 6. Bc4 { allows us to go } 6... Nbxd5 7. exd5 Bb4+ 8. Bd2 ( 8. Kf1 d6 { I like this move preparing to meet Qd4 with Bc5 and Ng4. The drawback is that our king is still in the center. } 9. Qe2+ Kf8 10. Nxd4 Bc5 11. Be3 h5 $11 { We will go Ng4 next or h4 and Rh5. } ) 8... Qe7+ { We force the exchange of queens. } 9. Qe2 Bxd2+ 10. Kxd2 Qxe2+ 11. Kxe2 c5 12. dxc6 bxc6 { We will get both d5 and c5 next. These pawns are definitely a strength for us in the endgame. } 13. Nxd4 d5 14. Bd3 $1 { Although this looks dangerous as the bishop can get trapped White is able to trade the bishops tactically. } 14... c5 15. Nb5 c4 16. Bf5 $1 Bxf5 17. Nd6+ Kd7 18. Nxf5 Rae8+ $11 { [%cal Ge8e5] } ) 6... Qxf6 7. Bc4 ( 7. a3 Nc6 8. Bd3 d6 { We want to go Bg4. } 9. Bb5 ( 9. h3 { allows us to go } 9... Rg8 $15 { [%cal Gg7g5] } ) 9... Bg4 10. Qxd4 Be7 $11 { We willl castle queenside next with an equal endgame. } ) 7... Bc5 { We will hold on to the d4 pawn now. } 8. O-O d6 9. e5 dxe5 10. Bg5 Qf5 ( 10... Qd6 { This is the more fighting option. } 11. Re1 O-O 12. Rxe5 Be6 13. Bxe6 fxe6 $36 { [%cal Ga8e8] } ) 11. Re1 Bd6 12. c3 O-O $1 { Our king is safe now and we will go e4 next. } 13. cxb4 e4 14. Nd2 Qxg5 15. Nxe4 Qh6 16. Nxd6 Qxd6 $36 { White will probably win back one of the pawns but we will have the initiative in the endgame. } ) 5... Bb4 6. Nxc6 bxc6 7. Bd3 ( 7. Bd2 Qe7 { We are ready to go for the move d5 next. } 8. Bd3 Bxc3 9. bxc3 d5 $11 { [%cal Gd5e4] } ) 7... d5 { We get good control over the center here and the game usually revolves around whether our central pawns are a boon or a curse. } 8. exd5 ( 8. Bd2 { This has been seen frequently over the last few years. It is mainly a drawing weapon as Black just needs to know a couple of details in the endgame. However, we can keep the game going with the Rb8 plan. } 8... O-O 9. O-O { White's threat is now to take on d5. } 9... Rb8 $5 { We defend the bishop on b4 and bring our rook to the open file. } ( 9... Bxc3 { the most direct way to equalize } 10. Bxc3 dxe4 $1 11. Bxf6 ( 11. Bc4 Bf5 $11 ) 11... Qxf6 12. Bxe4 Qxb2 13. Bxc6 Rb8 14. Rb1 Qxb1 15. Qxb1 Rxb1 16. Rxb1 Rd8 17. Bf3 Kf8 18. Rb8 Re8 19. h4 Ba6 20. Rb3 Be2 21. Bxe2 Rxe2 22. Rc3 Re7 23. f3 Ke8 24. Kf2 Kd7 { 1/2-1/2 (52) So,W (2765) -Carlsen,M (2872) Wijk aan Zee 2020 } 25. Re3 Rxe3 26. Kxe3 Kc6 $11 ) 10. Re1 Re8 { We are okay with allowing the move e5 in these positions generally as it is more of a weakness. White has a few options. } 11. a3 ( 11. exd5 { Releases the tension which White really wanted to maintain. } 11... cxd5 12. Rxe8+ Qxe8 13. Bg5 Ne4 $11 ) ( 11. h3 dxe4 ( 11... Be6 { Magnus wanted to play for a win but it gives White a slightly better position. } 12. b3 Nd7 13. exd5 cxd5 { 1/2-1/2 (33) Tari,A (2654) -Carlsen,M (2864) Stavanger 2022 } 14. Nb5 $14 ) 12. Nxe4 ( 12. Bxe4 Bxh3 $1 13. gxh3 Bxc3 14. Bxh7+ Kxh7 15. Rxe8 Qxe8 16. Bxc3 Qe6 $11 { We can try to exploit the weaknesses on the kingside. } ) 12... Nxe4 13. Bxb4 Nxf2 $1 { A desperado sacrifice! } 14. Rxe8+ Qxe8 15. Qe1 Qxe1+ 16. Rxe1 Be6 $11 { We are up a pawn but we will get an opposite colour bishop endgame which is likely to be a draw. } ) 11... Bg4 $1 { We force White to create a weakness or misplace his queen. } ( 11... Bxc3 { still leads to an equal endgame. } 12. Bxc3 dxe4 13. Bxe4 Qxd1 14. Raxd1 Nxe4 15. Rxe4 Bf5 16. Rxe8+ Rxe8 17. h3 Bxc2 18. Rd7 Rc8 19. Rd4 { 1-0 (71) Karjakin,S (2750) -Rapport,R (2747) Saint Louis 2019 } 19... a6 $11 ) 12. Qc1 { We have two options here. } ( 12. f3 Bc5+ 13. Kh1 Bh5 { The bishop will be well placed on g6. } 14. Rb1 Bb6 15. b4 dxe4 16. Nxe4 Bg6 17. Bc3 Nd5 18. Bd2 Nf6 $11 ) 12... Bxc3 ( 12... dxe4 13. Nxe4 Bxd2 14. Nxd2 Rxe1+ 15. Qxe1 Rxb2 $11 ) 13. Bxc3 dxe4 14. Bf1 h6 $11 { White has compensation for the pawn and the position is dynamically balanced. } ) 8... O-O { There is no need to recapture the pawn immediately. White cannot keep his king in the center any longer if he wants to fight for the advantage. } 9. O-O ( 9. dxc6 Bg4 10. Qd2 ( 10. f3 Re8+ 11. Kf1 ( 11. Be2 Nd5 $15 ) 11... Be6 12. Be3 Nd5 13. Nxd5 Bxd5 { We will win back the pawn on c6 next and we have very good compensation for the missing pawn with the White king on f1. } 14. Be4 { White gives up the f3 pawn but this leads to easy equality after we win c6. } 14... Bxe4 15. Qxd8 Raxd8 16. fxe4 Rxe4 $11 { [%cal Gd8d6,Gd6c6] } ) 10... Re8+ 11. Kf1 Qd6 { We keep all the material on the board. } ( 11... Ne4 $5 { This forces simplifications and a draw is very likely. } 12. Bxe4 Bxc3 13. bxc3 Rxe4 14. Qxd8+ Rxd8 $11 { [%csl Rc2,Rc3,Rc6][%cal Ge4c4] } ) 12. h3 Bh5 13. Qf4 Re5 $1 { We will soon double on the 'e' file. } 14. Bd2 Bxc3 15. bxc3 ( 15. Bxc3 $2 Re1+ $19 ) 15... Bg6 $44 { [%cal Ga8e8] } ) 9... cxd5 { This is very popular position across all levels. It is usually played to be very solid as White and he is okay with a draw. We will not be desperate but will try to keep the game going for as long as possible. I think the position is already equal as our center compensates for White's better placed pieces. } 10. Bg5 { This is the most common move not giving us the chance to go h6. Now the d5 pawn is under fire. } ( 10. Qf3 Bg4 11. Qg3 c5 $1 { We want to take on c3 followed by c4 and the bishop on d3 lacks a good square. } 12. Bg5 $5 { leads to mass simplifications after } 12... Bxc3 13. bxc3 c4 14. Bxh7+ Kxh7 15. Bxf6 Qxf6 16. Qxg4 Qxc3 { We reach a level endgame. } 17. Rad1 ( 17. Qh5+ Kg8 18. Qxd5 Rfd8 $11 ) 17... Rad8 18. Rd4 Kg8 19. Qd1 Rfe8 20. h4 Re5 $11 { This happened in the game 1/2-1/2 (59) Dubov,D (2708) -Paravyan,D (2584) Chess.com INT 2023. I would already take Black with his pawns in the center. } ) ( 10. h3 { White stops the move Bg4. } 10... h6 $5 { We can do the same and get our bishop to d6. } 11. Qf3 c6 12. Bf4 Bd6 { We want to trade the dark-squared bishops as the bishop on f4 was very well placed. } 13. Rfe1 Bxf4 14. Qxf4 c5 { We play actively with our central pawns. } 15. Rab1 ( 15. b3 Bd7 { The queen is heading to b8 to get the queen away from f4. } 16. Nb5 Qb8 17. Qxb8 Raxb8 18. a4 a5 $11 ) 15... Be6 16. b4 { White is trying to fight for the d4 square. } 16... d4 17. Ne4 Nd5 18. Qe5 Nxb4 19. Nxc5 Nxd3 20. cxd3 Bxa2 $11 { We can go f6 next and bring our bishop back to f7. } ) 10... c6 { Both sides have different plans here. As Black, I like the plan of bringing the bishop back to either d6 or f8 and eventually to go for the move c5. } 11. Qf3 { This is the most common move putting pressure on f6. } ( 11. h3 Bd6 { We get the bishop to its ideal square. } 12. Qf3 { transposes. } ) ( 11. Ne2 { The knight is heading to d4. } 11... h6 12. Bh4 Re8 { Here, we can get our bishop to f8 directly as the White knight is heading to d4. We want to be able to play c5 easily. } 13. Nd4 ( 13. c4 g5 14. Bg3 Ne4 $36 { [%cal Ge4d2] } ) 13... Bd7 { Bf8 and c5 is the threat now. } 14. c3 ( 14. Qf3 $6 g5 15. Bg3 Ne4 $15 ) 14... Bf8 { [%cal Gc6c5] } 15. Nf3 c5 $11 { [%cal Gd8b6] } ) ( 11. Na4 { White wants to get the move c4 and play against the d5 pawn. } 11... h6 12. Bh4 Re8 13. c4 ( 13. c3 Bd6 $11 ) 13... Rb8 { This is not a common move in this position. We get our rook to the semi-open file and can go Rb4 in the future. } 14. Rc1 Bd6 { We have brought our bishop back and d4 is a serious threat now. The knight is stuck on a4. } ( 14... d4 15. c5 { [%csl Rb4][%cal Gc1c4] } ) 15. cxd5 $1 ( 15. b3 d4 $1 16. Re1 Rxe1+ 17. Qxe1 c5 $15 ) 15... Rb4 { We attack the bishop on h4 forcing White to make a decision. } 16. Bxf6 ( 16. Bg3 Bxg3 17. hxg3 Qxd5 $11 { [%cal Gb4d4] } ) 16... Qxf6 17. Re1 ( 17. dxc6 { is pretty greedy. } 17... Rd4 $1 { White cannot get out of the pin easily as have ideas on the kingside too. } ( 17... Bxh2+ $4 18. Kxh2 Rh4+ 19. Kg1 Qf4 20. g3 $18 { The queen controls the d-h5 diagonal. } ) 18. Qc2 $2 { White looks fine but we can crash through on the kingside. } 18... Bxh2+ $1 19. Kxh2 Rh4+ 20. Kg1 Qf4 21. f3 ( 21. g3 Qf3 22. gxh4 Bh3 $19 ) 21... Qh2+ 22. Kf2 Bh3 23. Rg1 Rg4 $19 { There is no defence. } ) 17... Rxe1+ 18. Qxe1 Bf5 $1 19. Bxf5 Qxf5 { The a4 knight is under attack and we are also threatening to take on h2 followed by Qh5/Rh4. } 20. Qe8+ ( 20. dxc6 Bxh2+ 21. Kxh2 Rh4+ 22. Kg1 Qh5 $19 ) 20... Kh7 21. Qxc6 Bf4 22. Rf1 Bxh2+ 23. Kxh2 Qh5+ 24. Kg1 Rh4 25. Qc2+ f5 26. f3 Rh1+ 27. Kf2 Qh4+ 28. Ke2 Qe7+ $11 { leads to perpetual check. } ) 11... Bd6 { As I mentioned I like this plan the most. We can continue with either h6 or something like Rb8. We are waiting for White to do something with his pieces. Another plan is to go Be5 and get rid of the pin. } 12. h3 { This can occur via different move orders. I do not think it does too much for White in this position. } ( 12. Ne2 Be5 13. Rab1 h6 14. Bf4 Bg4 15. Qe3 Bxe2 16. Bxe2 Bxf4 17. Qxf4 Re8 $11 { [%cal Gd8b8,Gd8b6] I like our knight in this endgame and queen + knight is a great combination. } ) ( 12. Rfe1 Rb8 { The rook is usually activated along the 'b' file like b4 for example. } 13. Rab1 ( 13. Na4 $6 Rb4 14. b3 Rg4 $1 { A creative way of activating the rook. } 15. Bxf6 gxf6 $17 { The rook can always head to the 'e' file if needed after Rg5. } ) ( 13. b3 Bg4 { We force the trade of queens here. This is possible only after the move b3 as the c3 knight is hanging. } 14. Bxf6 Qxf6 15. Qxf6 ( 15. Qxg4 Qxc3 $11 ) 15... gxf6 16. Ne2 c5 $11 { The two bishops are enough compensation for the doubled pawns. } ) 13... h6 14. Bxf6 { This is similar to the main line. } ( 14. Bh4 Be6 15. Ne2 c5 16. b3 Rb4 $11 ) 14... Qxf6 15. Qxf6 gxf6 16. Ne2 c5 { These positions are usually completely fine for us with the bishop pair. } 17. b3 Be6 18. Ng3 Rfd8 { This is the typical regrouping to get the bishop to f8 defending the pawn on h6. } 19. Nf5 Bf8 20. Ne3 Bd6 21. g3 Kf8 22. Nf5 c4 23. bxc4 dxc4 24. Be4 Rxb1 25. Rxb1 Bc5 $11 ) ( 12. Rae1 { This is very common these days. White brings his a1 rook into the game in order to meet Rb8 with the move Nd1. He does not want to create unnecessary weaknesses. } 12... Be6 { We keep an eye on d5 preparing the move c5. We do not want to include the move Rb8 as it is not very important to our plan in the center. } ( 12... Rb8 13. Nd1 Be6 $11 { is also possible. } ) 13. Ne2 { This is a difference here compared to the position with the inclusion of Rb8 and Nd1. White tries to regroup the knight to d4. } 13... c5 { We stop Nd4 and create a potential threat of going c4 in the future.. } 14. b3 ( 14. Nf4 c4 15. Nh5 { This looks pretty dangerous but there is nothing too dangerous to be worried about on the kingside. } 15... cxd3 16. Nxf6+ gxf6 17. Bxf6 Qc7 18. Qh5 Bxh2+ 19. Kh1 Qf4 20. Be5 Qf5 $11 { [%cal Gh5h2,Gd3c2] } ) 14... h6 15. Bxf6 ( 15. Bh4 { allows } 15... g5 16. Bg3 Bg4 17. Qe3 Re8 { The queen is getting kicked around with a tempo. } 18. Qc1 Rc8 $11 ) 15... Qxf6 16. Qxf6 gxf6 { This is a trade which we have seen before. The two bishops compensate for our pawn structure on the kingside. } 17. Ng3 Rfd8 18. Nf5 Bf8 $11 ) 12... h6 { We want White to clarify his intentions regarding the g5 bishop. } 13. Bxf6 { This is usually played by people who want to make a draw with White. While it is true that these positions are completely even, it is not a foregone conclusion that the game ends in a draw. We do have the bishop pair after all. } ( 13. Bh4 Rb8 14. Rab1 Re8 { White has to take on f6 at some point as the threat now is to go g5-g4 trapping the queen. } 15. Ne2 $2 g5 16. Bg3 g4 $19 { The queen is trapped. } ) ( 13. Bf4 Rb8 14. b3 Bxf4 15. Qxf4 Be6 $11 { We are ready to go for the move c5 now. } ) 13... Qxf6 14. Qxf6 gxf6 15. Ne2 c5 { We are threatening to trap the bishop on d3. } 16. b3 ( 16. Ng3 Be5 17. Rab1 c4 18. Bf5 Be6 $11 { We would love to see a trade on e6 improving our pawn structure. } ) 16... Be6 17. Rad1 Rfd8 18. Ng3 { We have a few different plans here. } ( 18. g4 h5 19. Bf5 Kg7 $11 ) 18... a5 ( 18... c4 19. bxc4 dxc4 20. Be4 Rab8 21. Nf5 Bf8 $11 ) 19. Nf5 Bf8 { There is still a lot to fight for here. We want to get both a4 and c4 in. } 20. Ne3 a4 $11 { [%cal Ga8b8,Gc5c4] } *[Event "?"]
