1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. Bb5 { I call this the Four Knights Spanish due to the bishop on b5. We have two major options- to copy White with Bg4 or to go Nd4. Whenever I was not well prepared I used to go Bb4 as those lines are easier to play without preparation. But they lead to slightly unpleasant positions. Nd4 equalises almost by force and will be my recommendation here. } 4... Nd4 5. Bc4 { This is the critical try for White to keep an eye on the f7 pawn. } ( 5. Nxe5 { is not good due to } 5... Qe7 6. f4 ( 6. Nf3 Nxb5 7. Nxb5 Qxe4+ $15 ) 6... Nxb5 7. Nxb5 d6 8. Nf3 Qxe4+ 9. Kf2 Ng4+ 10. Kg3 ( 10. Kg1 Qc6 $15 ) 10... Qg6 11. Nh4 Qf6 $15 { [%cal Gg7g5] We are ready to go for the move g5 next. White has to be very precise to even get a slightly worse position. } ) ( 5. Bd3 { Has been tried by a few good players in rapid and blitz. } 5... d6 6. O-O ( 6. Nxd4 { This has been played by Andreikin. } 6... exd4 7. Ne2 d5 $1 8. e5 Nd7 $15 { We win the pawn on e5 with a great position. } ) 6... Bg4 7. Be2 Bxf3 { We eliminate our light-squared bishop for the knight to get control over the d4 square. } 8. Bxf3 c6 9. d3 g6 { [%csl Rf3][%cal Gh7h5,Gf8h6] We want to go h5 next followed by Bh6 and exchange the dark-squared bishops. The bishop on f3 will remain an issue for White. } 10. Be3 Ne6 11. a4 h5 { [%cal Gf8h6] } 12. d4 exd4 13. Bxd4 Nxd4 14. Qxd4 Qe7 $11 { [%cal Ge7e5] The queen will go to e5 followed by Bh6 next. We have good control over the dark squares. } ) ( 5. O-O c6 { We kick the bishop back to go d6 next move followed by Bg4. } 6. Bc4 ( 6. Ba4 a5 7. a3 Bc5 $15 { The bishop is misplaced on a4. We will just go d6 next with a better position. } 8. Nxe5 $4 d6 9. Nd3 Bg4 $19 ) ( 6. Bd3 { White blocks his 'd' pawn voluntarily. } 6... Nxf3+ 7. Qxf3 Be7 { We want to castle followed by the d5 break in the center. } 8. Qg3 d6 9. Be2 h5 $5 { We want to go h4 and start our play on the queenside. } ( 9... O-O $11 ) 10. d3 h4 $36 ) 6... d6 { We maintain the tension in the center ready to go Bg4 next. } 7. h3 ( 7. Nxd4 exd4 8. Ne2 Nxe4 9. Nxd4 Be7 $11 { [%cal Gd6d5] } ) 7... Nxf3+ 8. Qxf3 g5 $1 { This is a typical idea whenever White combines the moves 0-0 and h3. You can check out the game Aronian-Kramnik from Candidates 2018 in the Berlin where Black played the same idea and won a masterpiece. It is not so bad here but we have the initiative. } 9. Ne2 ( 9. d4 g4 10. hxg4 Bxg4 11. Qe3 Rg8 $36 { We will conitnue with Qe7 followed by Qh3. We have clear play on the kingside. } ) 9... g4 10. hxg4 Bxg4 11. Qb3 { We allow this because we have the move } 11... d5 $1 12. exd5 b5 $1 13. Bd3 Qxd5 { We win the pawn back along with control over the center. } 14. c4 Qc5 15. cxb5 Be6 16. Qc3 Rd8 $36 { We have a nice lead in development even in the endgame. } ) ( 5. Nxd4 { This has been played even by Magnus but only when he needs a draw with White. White forces some simplification. } 5... exd4 6. e5 { This is the famous drawing weapon. } ( 6. Nd5 { is a strange try allowing us to trade queens. } 6... Nxd5 7. exd5 Qe7+ 8. Qe2 ( 8. Be2 d3 9. cxd3 Qf6 $11 { We do not need to win the pawn back anytime soon and will continue with Bd6 next. } ) 8... b6 { We are going after the pawn on d5 very quickly, } 9. O-O Bb7 10. Re1 ( 10. Qf3 Qe5 $15 ) 10... Bxd5 11. Bxd7+ Kd8 $1 12. Qxe7+ Bxe7 $11 { We can continue with the move c5 building a strong center. } ) 6... dxc3 7. exf6 Qxf6 ( 7... cxd2+ { is too greedy, } 8. Bxd2 Qxf6 9. O-O $18 { is very dangerous for black } ) 8. dxc3 Bc5 9. O-O ( 9. Qe2+ Qe6 10. O-O ( 10. Bf4 { This was played by Magnus. } 10... c6 11. Bd3 d5 $11 { We can take on e2 next move with a completely even endgame. } ) 10... Qxe2 ( 10... O-O { can be played if you want to keep the queens on for now. } ) 11. Bxe2 d6 $11 { The endgame is completely equal. } ) 9... O-O 10. Qh5 ( 10. Bd3 h6 $11 { We can just continue with the move d5 next. } ) ( 10. Bxd7 { This is quite greedy as we have very good play with our lead in development against the pawn on f2. } 10... Bxd7 11. Qxd7 Rae8 { We are currently threatening mate in 2. } 12. Qd3 Re6 { White is still unable to develop the bishop and we are ready to go Bd2 next. } 13. Qc4 Bb6 $11 ) 10... d6 11. Qg5 { White forces the trade of queens. } ( 11. Bd3 h6 $11 ) ( 11. Bg5 $6 { does not help White after } 11... Qe5 { [%cal Gh7h6] } 12. Rae1 $2 { allows us to go } 12... Bxf2+ $19 ) 11... Qxg5 12. Bxg5 h6 13. Bd2 a5 $11 { There is nothing much to play for in this endgame. } ) ( 5. Ba4 { White keeps the bishop on this diagonal not allowing us to go d6. } 5... c6 { This is always a useful move for us with the knight on d4. } 6. Nxe5 { This is the critical line winning the pawn back but White wasted too much time } ( 6. O-O { is too slow here. } 6... a5 $1 7. Bb3 d6 $15 ) ( 6. d3 { is also quite slow. } 6... a5 7. Bb3 d6 $11 ) 6... d6 ( 6... d5 { is also good } 7. d3 Bc5 8. O-O O-O 9. Kh1 Qc7 10. f4 b5 11. Bb3 a5 12. a3 Nxb3 13. cxb3 { 1/2-1/2 (45) Duda,J (2748) -Grischuk,A (2764) Hamburg 2019 } 13... Re8 $44 ) 7. Nf3 ( 7. Nd3 { White does not allow the pin with Bg4 but this makes it harder to develop the c1 bishop. } 7... b5 8. Bb3 a5 { [%cal Ga5a4] } 9. Ne2 $1 { White needs to try to get rid of the knight on d4. This is a difficult move to play though as a4 was a threat. } ( 9. a3 $2 { allows the strong } 9... d5 $1 10. exd5 Bd6 $19 { We are going to castle next with a winning advantage. } ) 9... Bg4 $1 ( 9... Nxe2 $6 10. Qxe2 a4 11. e5 $13 ) 10. f3 Bxf3 11. gxf3 Nxf3+ 12. Kf2 Nh4 $36 { White has to be very precise to survive here. We are threatening both Ne4 and the move a4 trapping the bishop on b3. } ) 7... Bg4 8. d3 { White wants to go Be3 next and clarify the tension regarding the pin. } ( 8. h3 $6 Bxf3 9. gxf3 g6 10. d3 Bg7 11. Be3 Nh5 $17 { [%cal Gd8h4,Ge7h4,Ge8g8,Gf7f5] } ) 8... Bh5 $1 { This is a clever prophylactic move. We anticipate taking on f3 in the future with the knight and we do not want gxf3 to come with a tempo. Our plan now is to go Nd7-e5. } ( 8... Nd7 { runs into } 9. Be3 $16 ) 9. Rg1 { This is an awkward move to play but White wants to go g4 next. } ( 9. O-O $4 { allows } 9... Nd7 $19 { [%csl Rd1, Rf3,Rh5][%cal Gh5d1] } ) ( 9. Be3 $2 { This is not good here due to } 9... Nxf3+ 10. gxf3 d5 $17 { We exploit the bishop on e3 creating a threat of d4. } ) ( 9. h3 { White wants to go g4 next and we stop it with } 9... Nxf3+ 10. gxf3 { We have a few good options here. } 10... Be7 { This is the simplest as we get our king to safety. } 11. Rg1 ( 11. Bb3 d5 $11 ) 11... O-O 12. Bb3 Kh8 { Our king is pretty safe now. We will go Nd7-e5 next. } 13. Qd2 $1 { An important move to maintain clean equality. } 13... Nd7 14. Rxg7 $1 Bg6 { We are going to win the rook but our dark squares are a bit weak. } 15. Rxg6 fxg6 16. Qe3 Nc5 $11 { White has just enough compensation for the exchange. We will go a5-a4 next. } ) 9... b5 10. Nxd4 $1 { This is the best for White here giving up the queen. } ( 10. Bb3 a5 11. g4 $1 Bxg4 12. Bxf7+ Kxf7 13. Rxg4 Nxc2+ $1 14. Qxc2 Nxg4 { White has some compensation but he is the one who has to struggle to prove it. } 15. d4 Kg8 $11 ) 10... Bxd1 11. Nxc6 Qd7 12. Bxb5 a6 13. Ba4 Bxc2 14. b3 $1 { It is hard to stop White's threat of moving the knight. } 14... Bxd3 ( 14... Qc7 15. Bg5 $13 ) 15. Nd4 Bb5 16. Ncxb5 O-O-O { Finally we get our of the pin but we had to give up quite some material. } 17. Be3 axb5 18. Bxb5 Qg4 { The position is crazy but White is able to escape with a perpetual on the queenside. } 19. Rc1+ Kb7 20. Bc6+ Ka6 21. Bb5+ $11 ) 5... Bc5 { We play actively getting our bishop out to the ideal c5 square. We are giving up the e5 pawn. } 6. Nxe5 { This is the critical move grabbing the central pawn. } ( 6. O-O { is harmless as we go } 6... d6 7. Nxd4 ( 7. Na4 Bg4 8. Be2 Nxe2+ 9. Qxe2 Nd7 $11 ) 7... Bxd4 8. d3 O-O $11 { We can continue with a5 and Be6 or go for c6 and d5. Black has no issues. } ) ( 6. d3 { White plays it slow and allows us to consolidate easily. } 6... d6 7. Na4 { This is the only move which may pose some problems but we have } ( 7. Nxd4 Bxd4 8. Qf3 ( 8. Ne2 Bb6 9. O-O c6 $11 10. Ng3 $6 { Was a mistake played in the game 0-1 Abdusattorov,N (2713) -So,W (2760) Chess.com INT 2022. We have the strong move } 10... h5 $17 { [%cal Gh5h4] } ) 8... O-O 9. O-O { This happened in the game 1-0 (79) Artemiev,V (2701) -Caruana,F (2764) Chess.com INT 2023. I like the move } 9... Be6 { We would love to open the 'f' file. } 10. Bb3 a5 $11 { A common move gaining space on the queenside. } ) ( 7. h3 { White wants to maintain the tension with the knights. } 7... a5 { We create a luft for the bishop on a7. } 8. O-O c6 { [%cal Gb7b5, Ga5a4] } 9. a4 O-O $11 { There is nothing to worry about in these positions. } ) 7... b5 $1 { There are a lot of pieces hanging here. White has to go } 8. Nxd4 bxc4 9. Nf5 Bxf5 10. exf5 cxd3 11. Nxc5 dxc5 12. cxd3 ( 12. Qxd3 Qxd3 13. cxd3 O-O-O $11 ) 12... Qd7 { The weak f5 and d3 pawns compensate for our doubled and isolated 'c' pawns. } 13. Qf3 O-O 14. O-O Rfd8 15. Be3 Qxd3 16. Rac1 Rab8 17. b3 Qa6 18. Bg5 ( 18. Rc2 Rd3 $11 ) 18... Qxa2 19. Bxf6 gxf6 20. Qg4+ Kh8 21. Qh4 Rd6 $11 { Black was comfortable in the game 0-1 (42) Nepomniachtchi,I (2776) -Nakamura,H (2745) Chess.com INT 2020. } ) 6... Qe7 { We are going after the pawn on e4 and we also want to play the move d5 opening the position for our pieces. } 7. Nf3 ( 7. Nxf7 { is a mistake } 7... d5 $1 8. Nxd5 Qxf7 $17 ) ( 7. Nd3 { is met with } 7... d5 8. Nxd5 Qxe4+ 9. Ne3 Bd6 $36 { We have a huge initiative with our active pieces. } 10. O-O $2 { This looks very natural but he is lost after the simple } 10... b5 11. Bb3 O-O $19 { [%cal Gc7c5] The bishop is dead on c1. } ) 7... d5 $1 { We open the diagonal for the bishop to come to g4. } 8. Bxd5 ( 8. Nxd5 { allows us to win the e4 pawn. } 8... Qxe4+ 9. Ne3 Bg4 10. Be2 Nxe2 11. Qxe2 O-O-O { We have the bishop pair and a big lead in development in return for the pawn. } 12. d3 ( 12. O-O Bxe3 13. fxe3 Qxc2 $17 ) 12... Qe6 13. Nxg4 ( 13. Ng5 { does not help White as we go } 13... Qc6 14. Nxg4 Qxg2 15. Nxf6 Qxh1+ 16. Qf1 Qc6 17. Nfe4 { 1-0 (36) Yu,Y (2738) -Sychev,K (2563) Moscow 2019 } 17... Rhe8 $36 { White again has to be very precise to survive. } ) 13... Qxe2+ 14. Kxe2 Nxg4 15. Be3 Rhe8 16. Rae1 Nxe3 17. fxe3 Rxe3+ $11 { We win the pawn back with an equal endgame. } ) 8... Bg4 { We want to castle queenside next and bring all our pieces into the game. } ( 8... Nxd5 9. Nxd4 $14 ) 9. d3 ( 9. h3 Bxf3 10. gxf3 c6 11. Bb3 Nh5 $36 { The kingside structure is ruined for White and we will go Qh4 next targeting f2. } ) 9... O-O-O { This is the main move in the position and it leads to a forced draw. Yet another one of those famous drawing methods. } ( 9... Nd7 $5 { I analysed this too in case I wanted to avoid a draw. I will give some of my analysis here. } 10. h3 $1 ( 10. Be3 Ne5 $17 ) ( 10. Bg5 Nxf3+ 11. gxf3 Qxg5 12. fxg4 Ne5 $36 { [%cal Gc7c6,Gg5f4] } ) 10... Bxf3 11. gxf3 c6 12. f4 { This is not an easy move to play on the board. White gives up a piece on d5 for his center and activity. } 12... Qh4 ( 12... cxd5 13. Nxd5 Qd8 14. c3 Ne6 15. d4 Be7 16. Rg1 g6 17. Qf3 Nc7 18. Ne3 b5 19. f5 $14 ) 13. Na4 $8 { Another important move. } 13... cxd5 14. Nxc5 Nxc5 15. Be3 dxe4 $1 { We give back the piece and win back some of the pawns. } ( 15... Nce6 16. exd5 ( 16. c3 Nb5 17. Qa4 a6 18. exd5 Nc7 19. Qe4+ Kd8 $36 { is great for Black } ) 16... Nf5 17. Qf3 Nfd4 18. Bxd4 Nxd4 19. Qe4+ Qe7 20. Kd2 Nb5 21. Rhe1 Qxe4 22. dxe4 Nc7 $14 { I do not like this position as White has 3 central pawns for the piece. } ) 16. Bxd4 Ne6 17. Be3 Nxf4 18. Qg4 { White forces the trade of queens. } 18... Qxg4 19. hxg4 Ng2+ 20. Kd2 Nxe3 21. fxe3 exd3 22. cxd3 $11 { White has a slight edge in the endgame but it should be holdable. } ) 10. Be3 ( 10. O-O c6 11. Bb3 Nd7 $17 { [%cal Gd7e5] The game is over once the knight lands on e5. } ) ( 10. Bb3 Nxe4 $1 11. Nxe4 f5 { White is forced to give up the queen but it is not enough. } 12. Nxd4 Bxd1 13. Nxf5 Qe5 $17 ) ( 10. Bg5 Rhe8 { All of our pieces are playing well here. } 11. Bb3 ( 11. O-O Qd7 $17 { Bxf3 followed by Qh3 is a killing threat. } ) 11... Bh5 { We have already seen this prophylactic idea. } ( 11... Nxf3+ $1 12. gxf3 Bh5 13. Qe2 $16 ) 12. Kf1 h6 13. Be3 Nxf3 14. gxf3 Bb4 $15 { [%cal Gf6d7,Gb4c3,Gf6e4] We will go Nd7 next. } ) 10... Nxd5 11. Nxd5 ( 11. exd5 $2 { runs into } 11... Bxf3 12. gxf3 Nf5 $17 ) 11... Rxd5 $1 { We want to open the 'e' file. } 12. exd5 Re8 { Our big threat here is to go Qf6 next and win f3. We needed the rook on e8 to stop Bxd4. } 13. O-O { The king has finally castled and we can take on f3. } ( 13. c3 Nxf3+ 14. gxf3 Qh4 $1 { The king is now forced to run to the queenside. } 15. Kd2 Rxe3 16. fxe3 Qf2+ 17. Kc1 ( 17. Qe2 $4 Bxe3+ $19 ) 17... Bxf3 18. Qe1 Bxe3+ 19. Kb1 Bxh1 20. Qxh1 Qe2 { White cannot defend the pawn on d3. } 21. a4 Qxd3+ 22. Ka2 Qc4+ $11 { 1/2-1/2 (23) Wei,Y (2736) -Ding,L (2805) Abidjan 2019 } ) 13... Bxf3 14. gxf3 Bd6 $1 { We are going after the h2 pawn now. } 15. f4 Qh4 { [%cal Gh4h3,Gg7g5] Qh3 is a killing threat and so is the move g5. } 16. Bxd4 ( 16. Kg2 Nxc2 $1 17. Qxc2 Qg4+ 18. Kh1 Qf3+ 19. Kg1 Qg4+ { 1/2-1/2 (19) Mamedov,R (2650) -Wang,H (2737) Poikovsky 2019 } ) 16... Bxf4 17. Kg2 { There are two ways to force the draw. } 17... Qg5+ ( 17... Qxh2+ 18. Kf3 Qh3+ 19. Kxf4 Qh2+ 20. Kf3 ( 20. Kf5 g6+ 21. Kf6 Qh4+ 22. Kg7 Qxd4+ 23. Kh6 Qh4+ 24. Kg7 Qd4+ $11 ) 20... Qh3+ 21. Kf4 Qh2+ 22. Kf3 Qh3+ 23. Kf4 { 1/2-1/2 (23) McShane,L (2682) -So,W (2767) Douglas 2019 } ) 18. Kf3 ( 18. Kh1 Qh4 19. Kg2 Qg5+ 20. Kh1 Qh4 21. Kg2 { 1/2-1/2 (21) Vallejo Pons,F (2693) -Caruana, F (2819) Karlsruhe/Baden Baden 2019 } ) 18... Qh5+ 19. Kxf4 Qxh2+ 20. Kf5 g6+ 21. Kg4 Qg2+ 22. Kf4 Qh2+ 23. Kg4 $11 { A nice repetition to finish our journey into the sidelines after 1...e5. This is one line which we should revise periodically as we had some forcing lines. } *[Event "?"]
